Abacus.description: A table or tray strewn with sand, anciently used for drawing, calculating, etc.

Abalone.description: A univalve mollusk of the genus Haliotis. The shell is lined with mother-of-pearl, and used for ornamental purposes; the sea-ear. Several large species are found on the coast of California, clinging closely to the rocks.

Abandon.description: To cast or drive out; to banish; to expel; to reject.

Abandonment.description: The act of abandoning, or the state of being abandoned; total desertion; relinquishment.

Abdomen.description: The belly, or that part of the body between the thorax and the pelvis. Also, the cavity of the belly, which is lined by the peritoneum, and contains the stomach, bowels, and other viscera. In man, often restricted to the part between the diaphragm and the commencement of the pelvis, the remainder being called the pelvic cavity.

Abdominal.description: Of or pertaining to the abdomen; ventral; as, the abdominal regions, muscles, cavity.

Abduct.description: To take away surreptitiously by force; to carry away (a human being) wrongfully and usually by violence; to kidnap.

Abed.description: In bed, or on the bed.

Abet.description: To instigate or encourage by aid or countenance; -- used in a bad sense of persons and acts; as, to abet an ill-doer; to abet one in his wicked courses; to abet vice; to abet an insurrection.

Abhor.description: To shrink back with shuddering from; to regard with horror or detestation; to feel excessive repugnance toward; to detest to extremity; to loathe.

Ability.description: The quality or state of being able; power to perform, whether physical, moral, intellectual, conventional, or legal; capacity; skill or competence in doing; sufficiency of strength, skill, resources, etc.; -- in the plural, faculty, talent.

Ably.description: In an able manner; with great ability; as, ably done, planned, said.

Abnormal.description: Not conformed to rule or system; deviating from the type; anomalous; irregular.

Abnormality.description: The state or quality of being abnormal; variation; irregularity.

Abolitionism.description: The principles or measures of abolitionists.

Abominable.description: Worthy of, or causing, abhorrence, as a thing of evil omen; odious in the utmost degree; very hateful; detestable; loathsome; execrable.

Abort.description: To miscarry; to bring forth young prematurely.

Abracadabra.description: A mystical word or collocation of letters written as in the figure. Worn on an amulet it was supposed to ward off fever. At present the word is used chiefly in jest to denote something without meaning; jargon.

Abrupt.description: Broken off; very steep, or craggy, as rocks, precipices, banks; precipitous; steep; as, abrupt places.

Abruptly.description: In an abrupt manner; without giving notice, or without the usual forms; suddenly.

Abscond.description: To hide, withdraw, or be concealed.

Absent.description: Being away from a place; withdrawn from a place; not present.

Absenteeism.description: The state or practice of an absentee; esp. the practice of absenting one's self from the country or district where one's estate is situated.

Absolutist.description: One who is in favor of an absolute or autocratic government.

Absorb.description: To swallow up; to engulf; to overwhelm; to cause to disappear as if by swallowing up; to use up; to include.

Abstinent.description: Refraining from indulgence, especially from the indulgence of appetite; abstemious; continent; temperate.

Abundant.description: Fully sufficient; plentiful; in copious supply; -- followed by in, rarely by with.

Abundantly.description: In a sufficient degree; fully; amply; plentifully; in large measure.

Abuse.description: To put to a wrong use; to misapply; to misuse; to put to a bad use; to use for a wrong purpose or end; to pervert; as, to abuse inherited gold; to make an excessive use of; as, to abuse one's authority.

Abuser.description: One who abuses [in the various senses of the verb].

Abut.description: To project; to terminate or border; to be contiguous; to meet; -- with on, upon, or against; as, his land abuts on the road.

Abysmal.description: Pertaining to, or resembling, an abyss; bottomless; unending; profound.

Academy.description: A garden or grove near Athens (so named from the hero Academus), where Plato and his followers held their philosophical conferences; hence, the school of philosophy of which Plato was head.

Accent.description: A superior force of voice or of articulative effort upon some particular syllable of a word or a phrase, distinguishing it from the others.

Accept.description: To receive with a consenting mind (something offered); as, to accept a gift; -- often followed by of.

Acceptability.description: The quality of being acceptable; acceptableness.

Acceptable.description: Capable, worthy, or sure of being accepted or received with pleasure; pleasing to a receiver; gratifying; agreeable; welcome; as, an acceptable present, one acceptable to us.

Acceptably.description: In an acceptable manner; in a manner to please or give satisfaction.

Accident.description: Literally, a befalling; an event that takes place without one's foresight or expectation; an undesigned, sudden, and unexpected event; chance; contingency; often, an undesigned and unforeseen occurrence of an afflictive or unfortunate character; a casualty; a mishap; as, to die by an accident.

Accidental.description: Happening by chance, or unexpectedly; taking place not according to the usual course of things; casual; fortuitous; as, an accidental visit.

Accumulate.description: To heap up in a mass; to pile up; to collect or bring together; to amass; as, to accumulate a sum of money.

Accumulation.description: The act of accumulating, the state of being accumulated, or that which is accumulated; as, an accumulation of earth, of sand, of evils, of wealth, of honors.

Accumulative.description: Characterized by accumulation; serving to collect or amass; cumulative; additional.

Accumulator.description: One who, or that which, accumulates, collects, or amasses.

Accusatory.description: Pertaining to, or containing, an accusation; as, an accusatory libel.

Acetic.description: Of a pertaining to vinegar; producing vinegar; producing vinegar; as, acetic fermentation.

Acid.description: Sour, sharp, or biting to the taste; tart; having the taste of vinegar: as, acid fruits or liquors. Also fig.: Sour-tempered.

Acidic.description: Containing a high percentage of silica; -- opposed to basic.

Acidify.description: To make acid; to convert into an acid; as, to acidify sugar.

Acidity.description: The quality of being sour; sourness; tartness; sharpness to the taste; as, the acidity of lemon juice.

Acme.description: The top or highest point; the culmination.

Acne.description: A pustular affection of the skin, due to changes in the sebaceous glands.

Acorn.description: The fruit of the oak, being an oval nut growing in a woody cup or cupule.

Acrid.description: Sharp and harsh, or bitter and not, to the taste; pungent; as, acrid salts.

Acrimony.description: A quality of bodies which corrodes or destroys others; also, a harsh or biting sharpness; as, the acrimony of the juices of certain plants.

Acrobat.description: One who practices rope dancing, high vaulting, or other daring gymnastic feats.

Acropolis.description: The upper part, or the citadel, of a Grecian city; especially, the citadel of Athens.

Acrylic.description: Of or containing acryl, the hypothetical radical of which acrolein is the hydride; as, acrylic acid.

Activity.description: The state or quality of being active; nimbleness; agility; vigorous action or operation; energy; active force; as, an increasing variety of human activities.

Acton.description: A stuffed jacket worn under the mail, or (later) a jacket plated with mail.

Actualize.description: To make actual; to realize in action.

Actuate.description: To put into action or motion; to move or incite to action; to influence actively; to move as motives do; -- more commonly used of persons.

Actuator.description: One who actuates, or puts into action.

Acute.description: Sharp at the end; ending in a sharp point; pointed; -- opposed to blunt or obtuse; as, an acute angle; an acute leaf.

Acutely.description: In an acute manner; sharply; keenly; with nice discrimination.

Adagio.description: Slow; slowly, leisurely, and gracefully. When repeated, adagio, adagio, it directs the movement to be very slow.

Adam.description: The name given in the Bible to the first man, the progenitor of the human race.

Adamant.description: A stone imagined by some to be of impenetrable hardness; a name given to the diamond and other substances of extreme hardness; but in modern mineralogy it has no technical signification. It is now a rhetorical or poetical name for the embodiment of impenetrable hardness.

Adar.description: The twelfth month of the Hebrew ecclesiastical year, and the sixth of the civil. It corresponded nearly with March.

Adept.description: One fully skilled or well versed in anything; a proficient; as, adepts in philosophy.

Adequacy.description: The state or quality of being adequate, proportionate, or sufficient; a sufficiency for a particular purpose; as, the adequacy of supply to the expenditure.

Admit.description: To suffer to enter; to grant entrance, whether into a place, or into the mind, or consideration; to receive; to take; as, they were into his house; to admit a serious thought into the mind; to admit evidence in the trial of a cause.

Adobe.description: An unburnt brick dried in the sun; also used as an adjective, as, an adobe house, in Texas or New Mexico.

Adonis.description: A youth beloved by Venus for his beauty. He was killed in the chase by a wild boar.

Adopt.description: To take by choice into relationship, as, child, heir, friend, citizen, etc.; esp. to take voluntarily (a child of other parents) to be in the place of, or as, one's own child.

Adorable.description: Deserving to be adored; worthy of divine honors.

Adorn.description: To deck or dress with ornaments; to embellish; to set off to advantage; to render pleasing or attractive.

Adornment.description: An adorning; an ornament; a decoration.

Adrian.description: Pertaining to the Adriatic Sea; as, Adrian billows.

Adriatic.description: Of or pertaining to a sea so named, the northwestern part of which is known as the Gulf of Venice.

Adrift.description: Floating at random; in a drifting condition; at the mercy of wind and waves. Also fig.

Adult.description: Having arrived at maturity, or to full size and strength; matured; as, an adult person or plant; an adult ape; an adult age.

Advent.description: The period including the four Sundays before Christmas.

Adventist.description: One of a religious body, embracing several branches, who look for the proximate personal coming of Christ; -- called also Second Adventists.

Advisability.description: The quality of being advisable; advisableness.

Advisable.description: Proper to be advised or to be done; expedient; prudent.

Advocacy.description: The act of pleading for or supporting; work of advocating; intercession.

Afar.description: At, to, or from a great distance; far away; -- often used with from preceding, or off following; as, he was seen from afar; I saw him afar off.

Affix.description: To subjoin, annex, or add at the close or end; to append to; to fix to any part of; as, to affix a syllable to a word; to affix a seal to an instrument; to affix one's name to a writing.

Agency.description: The faculty of acting or of exerting power; the state of being in action; action; instrumentality.

Agent.description: Acting; -- opposed to patient, or sustaining, action.

Ageratum.description: A genus of plants, one species of which (A. Mexicanum) has lavender-blue flowers in dense clusters.

Agility.description: The quality of being agile; the power of moving the limbs quickly and easily; nimbleness; activity; quickness of motion; as, strength and agility of body.

Agnostic.description: Professing ignorance; involving no dogmatic; pertaining to or involving agnosticism.

Agonist.description: One who contends for the prize in public games.

Agrarian.description: Pertaining to fields, or lands, or their tenure; esp., relating to an equal or equitable division of lands; as, the agrarian laws of Rome, which distributed the conquered and other public lands among citizens.

Agronomist.description: One versed in agronomy; a student of agronomy.

Ahold.description: Near the wind; as, to lay a ship ahold.

Ajar.description: Slightly turned or opened; as, the door was standing ajar.

Akimbo.description: With a crook or bend; with the hand on the hip and elbow turned outward.

Akin.description: Of the same kin; related by blood; -- used of persons; as, the two families are near akin.

Alacrity.description: A cheerful readiness, willingness, or promptitude; joyous activity; briskness; sprightliness; as, the soldiers advanced with alacrity to meet the enemy.

Aland.description: On land; to the land; ashore.

Alarm.description: A summons to arms, as on the approach of an enemy.

Alarmist.description: One prone to sound or excite alarms, especially, needless alarms.

Alas.description: An exclamation expressive of sorrow, pity, or apprehension of evil; -- in old writers, sometimes followed by day or white; alas the day, like alack a day, or alas the white.

Alban.description: A white crystalline resinous substance extracted from gutta-percha by the action of alcohol or ether.

Albanian.description: Of or pertaining to Albania, a province of Turkey.

Albino.description: A person, whether negro, Indian, or white, in whom by some defect of organization the substance which gives color to the skin, hair, and eyes is deficient or in a morbid state. An albino has a skin of a milky hue, with hair of the same color, and eyes with deep red pupil and pink or blue iris. The term is also used of the lower animals, as white mice, elephants, etc.; and of plants in a whitish condition from the absence of chlorophyll.

Albion.description: An ancient name of England, still retained in poetry.

Album.description: A white tablet on which anything was inscribed, as a list of names, etc.

Alcazar.description: A fortress; also, a royal palace.

Alco.description: A small South American dog, domesticated by the aborigines.

Alcoholic.description: Of or pertaining to alcohol, or partaking of its qualities; derived from, or caused by, alcohol; containing alcohol; as, alcoholic mixtures; alcoholic gastritis; alcoholic odor.

Aleatory.description: Depending on some uncertain contingency; as, an aleatory contract.

Alfalfa.description: The lucern (Medicago sativa); -- so called in California, Texas, etc.

Algebra.description: That branch of mathematics which treats of the relations and properties of quantity by means of letters and other symbols. It is applicable to those relations that are true of every kind of magnitude.

Algol.description: A fixed star, in Medusa's head, in the constellation Perseus, remarkable for its periodic variation in brightness.

Alhambra.description: The palace of the Moorish kings at Granada.

Alias.description: Otherwise; otherwise called; -- a term used in legal proceedings to connect the different names of any one who has gone by two or more, and whose true name is for any cause doubtful; as, Smith, alias Simpson.

Alibi.description: The plea or mode of defense under which a person on trial for a crime proves or attempts to prove that he was in another place when the alleged act was committed; as, to set up an alibi; to prove an alibi.

Alien.description: Not belonging to the same country, land, or government, or to the citizens or subjects thereof; foreign; as, alien subjects, enemies, property, shores.

Alkahest.description: The fabled "universal solvent" of the alchemists; a menstruum capable of dissolving all bodies.

Alkali.description: Soda ash; caustic soda, caustic potash, etc.

Alkalinity.description: The quality which constitutes an alkali; alkaline property.

Almanac.description: A book or table, containing a calendar of days, and months, to which astronomical data and various statistics are often added, such as the times of the rising and setting of the sun and moon, eclipses, hours of full tide, stated festivals of churches, terms of courts, etc.

Almost.description: Nearly; well nigh; all but; for the greatest part.

Alms.description: Anything given gratuitously to relieve the poor, as money, food, or clothing; a gift of charity.

Aloft.description: On high; in the air; high above the ground.

Alpaca.description: An animal of Peru (Lama paco), having long, fine, wooly hair, supposed by some to be a domesticated variety of the llama.

Altaic.description: Of or pertaining to the Altai, a mountain chain in Central Asia.

Altimetry.description: The art of measuring altitudes, or heights.

Alto.description: Formerly the part sung by the highest male, or counter-tenor, voices; now the part sung by the lowest female, or contralto, voices, between in tenor and soprano. In instrumental music it now signifies the tenor.

Altruistic.description: Regardful of others; beneficent; unselfish; -- opposed to egoistic or selfish.

Alum.description: A double sulphate formed of aluminium and some other element (esp. an alkali metal) or of aluminium. It has twenty-four molecules of water of crystallization.

Alumina.description: One of the earths, consisting of two parts of aluminium and three of oxygen, Al2O3.

Alumna.description: A female pupil; especially, a graduate of a school or college.

Alumnus.description: A pupil; especially, a graduate of a college or other seminary of learning.

Amalgam.description: An alloy of mercury with another metal or metals; as, an amalgam of tin, bismuth, etc.

Amazon.description: One of a fabulous race of female warriors in Scythia; hence, a female warrior.

Amazonian.description: Pertaining to or resembling an Amazon; of masculine manners; warlike.

Babel.description: The city and tower in the land of Shinar, where the confusion of languages took place.

Babu.description: A Hindoo gentleman; a native clerk who writes English; also, a Hindoo title answering to Mr.  or Esquire.

Baby.description: An infant or young child of either sex; a babe.

Babylonian.description: Of or pertaining to the real or to the mystical Babylon, or to the ancient kingdom of Babylonia; Chaldean.

Bacon.description: The back and sides of a pig salted and smoked; formerly, the flesh of a pig salted or fresh.

Bacterium.description: A microscopic vegetable organism, belonging to the class Algae, usually in the form of a jointed rodlike filament, and found in putrefying organic infusions.  Bacteria are destitute of chlorophyll, and are the smallest of microscopic organisms. They are very widely diffused in nature, and multiply with marvelous rapidity, both by fission and by spores. Certain species are active agents in fermentation, while others appear to be the cause of certain infectious diseases. See Bacillus.

Cabin.description: A cottage or small house; a hut.

Cabinet.description: A hut; a cottage; a small house.

Cable.description: A large, strong rope or chain, of considerable length, used to retain a vessel at anchor, and for other purposes. It is made of hemp, of steel wire, or of iron links.

Cablegram.description: A message sent by a submarine telegraphic cable.

Cacao.description: A small evergreen tree (Theobroma Cacao) of South America and the West Indies. Its fruit contains an edible pulp, inclosing seeds about the size of an almond, from which cocoa, chocolate, and broma are prepared.

Cactus.description: Any plant of the order Cactacae, as the prickly pear and the night-blooming cereus. See Cereus. They usually have leafless stems and branches, often beset with clustered thorns, and are mostly natives of the warmer parts of America.

Cadet.description: The younger of two brothers; a younger brother or son; the youngest son.

Cadmium.description: A comparatively rare element related to zinc, and occurring in some zinc ores. It is a white metal, both ductile and malleable. Symbol Cd. Atomic weight 111.8. It was discovered by Stromeyer in 1817, who named it from its association with zinc or zinc ore.

Cadre.description: The framework or skeleton upon which a regiment is to be formed; the officers of a regiment forming the staff.

Cafe.description: A coffeehouse; a restaurant; also, a room in a hotel or restaurant where coffee and liquors are served.

Caftan.description: A garment worn throughout the Levant, consisting of a long gown with sleeves reaching below the hands. It is generally fastened by a belt or sash.

Calamity.description: Any great misfortune or cause of misery; -- generally applied to events or disasters which produce extensive evil, either to communities or individuals.

Calcify.description: To make stony or calcareous by the deposit or secretion of salts of lime.

Calcium.description: An elementary substance; a metal which combined with oxygen forms lime. It is of a pale yellow color, tenacious, and malleable. It is a member of the alkaline earth group of elements. Atomic weight 40. Symbol Ca.

Calculate.description: To ascertain or determine by mathematical processes, usually by the ordinary rules of arithmetic; to reckon up; to estimate; to compute.

Calculation.description: The act or process, or the result, of calculating; computation; reckoning, estimate.

Calculator.description: One who computes or reckons: one who estimates or considers the force and effect of causes, with a view to form a correct estimate of the effects.

Caledonia.description: The ancient Latin name of Scotland; -- still used in poetry.

Caledonian.description: Of or pertaining to Caledonia or Scotland; Scottish; Scotch.

Cali.description: The tenth avatar or incarnation of the god Vishnu.

Calico.description: Plain white cloth made from cotton, but which receives distinctive names according to quality and use, as, super calicoes, shirting calicoes, unbleached calicoes, etc.

Calkin.description: A calk on a shoe. See Calk, n., 1.

Ebony.description: A hard, heavy, and durable wood, which admits of a fine polish or gloss. The usual color is black, but it also occurs red or green.

Eccentric.description: Deviating or departing from the center, or from the line of a circle; as, an eccentric or elliptical orbit; pertaining to deviation from the center or from true circular motion.

Eccentricity.description: The state of being eccentric; deviation from the customary line of conduct; oddity.

Eclectic.description: Selecting; choosing (what is true or excellent in doctrines, opinions, etc.) from various sources or systems; as, an eclectic philosopher.

Fabian.description: Of, pertaining to, or in the manner of, the Roman general, Quintus Fabius Maximus Verrucosus; cautious; dilatory; avoiding a decisive contest.

Fable.description: A Feigned story or tale, intended to instruct or amuse; a fictitious narration intended to enforce some useful truth or precept; an apologue. See the Note under Apologue.

Fabric.description: The structure of anything; the manner in which the parts of a thing are united; workmanship; texture; make; as cloth of a beautiful fabric.

Fabulous.description: Feigned, as a story or fable; related in fable; devised; invented; not real; fictitious; as, a fabulous description; a fabulous hero.

Facet.description: A little face; a small, plane surface; as, the facets of a diamond.

Facility.description: The quality of being easily performed; freedom from difficulty; ease; as, the facility of an operation.

Facsimile.description: A copy of anything made, either so as to be deceptive or so as to give every part and detail of the original; an exact copy or likeness.

Facto.description: In fact; by the act or fact.

Faculty.description: Ability to act or perform, whether inborn or cultivated; capacity for any natural function; especially, an original mental power or capacity for any of the well-known classes of mental activity; psychical or soul capacity; capacity for any of the leading kinds of soul activity, as knowledge, feeling, volition; intellectual endowment or gift; power; as, faculties of the mind or the soul.

Falcon.description: One of a family (Falconidae) of raptorial birds, characterized by a short, hooked beak, strong claws, and powerful flight.

Falconet.description: One of the smaller cannon used in the 15th century and later.

Falconry.description: The art of training falcons or hawks to pursue and attack wild fowl or game.

Falsify.description: To make false; to represent falsely.

Falsity.description: The quality of being false; coutrariety or want of conformity to truth.

Familiarity.description: The state of being familiar; intimate and frequent converse, or association; unconstrained intercourse; freedom from ceremony and constraint; intimacy; as, to live in remarkable familiarity.

Family.description: The collective body of persons who live in one house, and under one head or manager; a household, including parents, children, and servants, and, as the case may be, lodgers or boarders.

Fanatic.description: Pertaining to, or indicating, fanaticism; extravagant in opinions; ultra; unreasonable; excessively enthusiastic, especially on religious subjects; as, fanatic zeal; fanatic notions.

Fanatical.description: Characteristic of, or relating to, fanaticism; fanatic.

Fanciful.description: Full of fancy; guided by fancy, rather than by reason and experience; whimsical; as, a fanciful man forms visionary projects.

Fancy.description: The faculty by which the mind forms an image or a representation of anything perceived before; the power of combining and modifying such objects into new pictures or images; the power of readily and happily creating and recalling such objects for the purpose of amusement, wit, or embellishment; imagination.

Fandango.description: A lively dance, in 3-8 or 6-8 time, much practiced in Spain and Spanish America. Also, the tune to which it is danced.

Fangle.description: Something new-fashioned; a foolish innovation; a gewgaw; a trifling ornament.

Fangled.description: New made; hence, gaudy; showy; vainly decorated. [Obs., except with the prefix new.] See Newfangled.

Fantastic.description: Existing only in imagination; fanciful; imaginary; not real; chimerical.

Fantasy.description: Fancy; imagination; especially, a whimsical or fanciful conception; a vagary of the imagination; whim; caprice; humor.

Farcical.description: Pertaining to farce; appropriated to farce; ludicrous; unnatural; unreal.

Farm.description: The rent of land, -- originally paid by reservation of part of its products.

Farmyard.description: The yard or inclosure attached to a barn, or the space inclosed by the farm buildings.

Faro.description: A gambling game at cardds, in whiich all the other players play against the dealer or banker, staking their money upon the order in which the cards will lie and be dealt from the pack.

Fast.description: To abstain from food; to omit to take nourishment in whole or in part; to go hungry.

Fatal.description: Proceeding from, or appointed by, fate or destiny; necessary; inevitable.

Fatalist.description: One who maintains that all things happen by inevitable necessity.

Fatalistic.description: Implying, or partaking of the nature of, fatalism.

Fatality.description: The state of being fatal, or proceeding from destiny; invincible necessity, superior to, and independent of, free and rational control.

Fated.description: Decreed by fate; destined; doomed; as, he was fated to rule a factious people.

Fatuous.description: Feeble in mind; weak; silly; stupid; foolish; fatuitous.

Favoritism.description: The disposition to favor and promote the interest of one person or family, or of one class of men, to the neglect of others having equal claims; partiality.

Fealty.description: Fidelity to one's lord; the feudal obligation by which the tenant or vassal was bound to be faithful to his lord; the special oath by which this obligation was assumed; fidelity to a superior power, or to a government; loyality. It is no longer the practice to exact the performance of fealty, as a feudal obligation.

Fecal.description: relating to, or containing, dregs, feces, or ordeure; faecal.

Fecundity.description: The quality or power of producing fruit; fruitfulness; especially (Biol.), the quality in female organisms of reproducing rapidly and in great numbers.

Federalism.description: the principles of Federalists or of federal union.

Felicity.description: The state of being happy; blessedness; blissfulness; enjoyment of good.

Felis.description: A genus of carnivorous mammals, including the domestic cat, the lion, tiger, panther, and similar animals.

Felon.description: A person who has committed a felony.

Felony.description: An act on the part of the vassal which cost him his fee by forfeiture.

Femininity.description: The quality or nature of the female sex; womanliness.

Fenian.description: A member of a secret organization, consisting mainly of Irishment, having for its aim the overthrow of English rule in ireland.

Feral.description: Wild; untamed; ferine; not domesticated; -- said of beasts, birds, and plants.

Feria.description: A week day, esp. a day which is neither a festival nor a fast.

Fescue.description: A straw, wire, stick, etc., used chiefly to point out letters to children when learning to read.

Festival.description: Pertaining to a fest; festive; festal; appropriate to a festival; joyous; mirthful.

Festivity.description: The condition of being festive; social joy or exhilaration of spirits at an entertaintment; joyfulness; gayety.

Fetal.description: Pertaining to, or connected with, a fetus; as, fetal circulation; fetal membranes.

Fetishism.description: The doctrine or practice of belief in fetiches.

Fetus.description: The young or embryo of an animal in the womb, or in the egg; often restricted to the later stages in the development of viviparous and oviparous animals, embryo being applied to the earlier stages.

Feud.description: A combination of kindred to avenge injuries or affronts, done or offered to any of their blood, on the offender and all his race.

Feudal.description: Of or pertaining to feuds, fiefs, or feels; as, feudal rights or services; feudal tenures.

Fiasco.description: A complete or ridiculous failure, esp. of a musical performance, or of any pretentious undertaking.

Fiat.description: An authoritative command or order to do something; an effectual decree.

Fibrin.description: A white, albuminous, fibrous substance, formed in the coagulation of the blood either by decomposition of fibrinogen, or from the union of fibrinogen and paraglobulin which exist separately in the blood. It is insoluble in water, but is readily digestible in gastric and pancreatic juice.

Fico.description: A fig; an insignificant trifle, no more than the snap of one's thumb; a sign of contempt made by the fingers, expressing. A fig for you.

Fidalgo.description: The lowest title of nobility in Portugal, corresponding to that of Hidalgo in Spain.

Fidelity.description: Faithfulness; adherence to right; careful and exact observance of duty, or discharge of obligations.

Fiduciary.description: One who holds a thing in trust for another; a trustee.

Fifty.description: Five times ten; as, fifty men.

Figment.description: An invention; a fiction; something feigned or imagined.

Fijian.description: Of or pertaining to the Fiji islands or their inhabitants.

Filament.description: A thread or threadlike object or appendage; a fiber; esp. (Bot.), the threadlike part of the stamen supporting the anther.

Filial.description: Of or pertaining to a son or daughter; becoming to a child in relation to his parents; as, filial obedience.

Film.description: A thin skin; a pellicle; a membranous covering, causing opacity; hence, any thin, slight covering.

Final.description: Pertaining to the end or conclusion; last; terminating; ultimate; as, the final day of a school term.

Finality.description: The state of being final, finished, or complete; a final or conclusive arrangement; a settlement.

Find.description: To meet with, or light upon, accidentally; to gain the first sight or knowledge of, as of something new, or unknown; hence, to fall in with, as a person.

Fiscal.description: Pertaining to the public treasury or revenue.

Fisk.description: To run about; to frisk; to whisk.

Fist.description: The hand with the fingers doubled into the palm; the closed hand, especially as clinched tightly for the purpose of striking a blow.

Fitful.description: Full of fits; irregularly variable; impulsive and unstable.

Fitz.description: A son; -- used in compound names, to indicate paternity, esp. of the illegitimate sons of kings and princes of the blood; as, Fitzroy, the son of the king; Fitzclarence, the son of the duke of Clarence.

Fixation.description: The act of fixing, or the state of being fixed.

Fixative.description: That which serves to set or fix colors or drawings, as a mordant.

Flaccid.description: Yielding to pressure for want of firmness and stiffness; soft and weak; limber; lax; drooping; flabby; as, a flaccid muscle; flaccid flesh.

Flag.description: To hang loose without stiffness; to bend down, as flexible bodies; to be loose, yielding, limp.

Flagman.description: One who makes signals with a flag.

Flaky.description: Consisting of flakes or of small, loose masses; lying, or cleaving off, in flakes or layers; flakelike.

Flam.description: A freak or whim; also, a falsehood; a lie; an illusory pretext; deception; delusion.

Flamingo.description: Any bird of the genus Phoenicopterus. The flamingoes have webbed feet, very long legs, and a beak bent down as if broken. Their color is usually red or pink. The American flamingo is P. ruber; the European is P. antiquorum.

Flank.description: The fleshy or muscular part of the side of an animal, between the ribs and the hip. See Illust. of Beef.

Flap.description: Anything broad and limber that hangs loose, or that is attached by one side or end and is easily moved; as, the flap of a garment.

Flask.description: A small bottle-shaped vessel for holding fluids; as, a flask of oil or wine.

Flat.description: Having an even and horizontal surface, or nearly so, without prominences or depressions; level without inclination; plane.

Flatly.description: In a flat manner; evenly; horizontally; without spirit; dully; frigidly; peremptorily; positively, plainly.

Flatulent.description: Affected with flatus or gases generated in the alimentary canal; windy.

Flavin.description: A yellow, vegetable dyestuff, resembling quercitron.

Flexion.description: The act of flexing or bending; a turning.

Flimflam.description: A freak; a trick; a lie.

Flimsy.description: Weak; feeble; limp; slight; vain; without strength or solidity; of loose and unsubstantial structure; without reason or plausibility; as, a flimsy argument, excuse, objection.

Flint.description: A massive, somewhat impure variety of quartz, in color usually of a gray to brown or nearly black, breaking with a conchoidal fracture and sharp edge. It is very hard, and strikes fire with steel.

Flinty.description: Consisting of, composed of, abounding in, or resembling, flint; as, a flinty rock; flinty ground; a flinty heart.

Flip.description: A mixture of beer, spirit, etc., stirred and heated by a hot iron.

Flit.description: To move with celerity through the air; to fly away with a rapid motion; to dart along; to fleet; as, a bird flits away; a cloud flits along.

Flog.description: To beat or strike with a rod or whip; to whip; to lash; to chastise with repeated blows.

Flop.description: To clap or strike, as a bird its wings, a fish its tail, etc.; to flap.

Flora.description: The goddess of flowers and spring.

Floral.description: Pertaining to Flora, or to flowers; made of flowers; as, floral games, wreaths.

Floren.description: A cerain gold coin; a Florence.

Florid.description: Covered with flowers; abounding in flowers; flowery.

Florin.description: A silver coin of Florence, first struck in the twelfth century, and noted for its beauty. The name is given to different coins in different countries. The florin of England, first minted in 1849, is worth two shillings, or about 48 cents; the florin of the Netherlands, about 40 cents; of Austria, about 36 cents.

Florist.description: A cultivator of, or dealer in, flowers.

Fluctuate.description: To move as a wave; to roll hither and thither; to wave; to float backward and forward, as on waves; as, a fluctuating field of air.

Fluency.description: The quality of being fluent; smoothness; readiness of utterance; volubility.

Fluent.description: Flowing or capable of flowing; liquid; glodding; easily moving.

Fluid.description: Having particles which easily move and change their relative position without a separation of the mass, and which easily yield to pressure; capable of flowing; liquid or gaseous.

Flunk.description: To fail, as on a lesson; to back out, as from an undertaking, through fear.

Flutist.description: A performer on the flute; a flautist.

Fluty.description: Soft and clear in tone, like a flute.

Fluvial.description: Belonging to rivers; growing or living in streams or ponds; as, a fluvial plant.

Fluxional.description: Pertaining to, or having the nature of, fluxion or fluxions; variable; inconstant.

Focal.description: Belonging to,or concerning, a focus; as, a focal point.

Focus.description: A point in which the rays of light meet, after being reflected or refrcted, and at which the image is formed; as, the focus of a lens or mirror.

Fogy.description: A dull old fellow; a person behind the times, over-conservative, or slow; -- usually preceded by old.

Fold.description: To lap or lay in plaits or folds; to lay one part over another part of; to double; as, to fold cloth; to fold a letter.

Foment.description: To apply a warm lotion to; to bathe with a cloth or sponge wet with warm water or medicated liquid.

Fondle.description: To treat or handle with tenderness or in a loving manner; to caress; as, a nurse fondles a child.

Font.description: A complete assortment of printing type of one size, including a due proportion of all the letters in the alphabet, large and small, points, accents, and whatever else is necessary for printing with that variety of types; a fount.

Forceps.description: A pair of pinchers, or tongs; an instrument for grasping, holding firmly, or exerting traction upon, bodies which it would be inconvenient or impracticable to seize with the fingers, especially one for delicate operations, as those of watchmakers, surgeons, accoucheurs, dentists, etc.

Forcible.description: Possessing force; characterized by force, efficiency, or energy; powerful; efficacious; impressive; influential.

Ford.description: A place in a river, or other water, where it may be passed by man or beast on foot, by wading.

Forest.description: An extensive wood; a large tract of land covered with trees; in the United States, a wood of native growth, or a tract of woodland which has never been cultivated.

Forestry.description: The art of forming or of cultivating forests; the management of growing timber.

Forgetful.description: Apt to forget; easily losing remembrance; as, a forgetful man should use helps to strengthen his memory.

Forgivable.description: Capable of being forgiven; pardonable; venial.

Forgo.description: To pass by; to leave. See 1st Forego.

Fork.description: An instrument consisting of a handle with a shank terminating in two or more prongs or tines, which are usually of metal, parallel and slightly curved; -- used from piercing, holding, taking up, or pitching anything.

Form.description: The shape and structure of anything, as distinguished from the material of which it is composed; particular disposition or arrangement of matter, giving it individuality or distinctive character; configuration; figure; external appearance.

Formalist.description: One overattentive to forms, or too much confined to them; esp., one who rests in external religious forms, or observes strictly the outward forms of worship, without possessing the life and spirit of religion.

Formality.description: The condition or quality of being formal, strictly ceremonious, precise, etc.

Formic.description: Pertaining to, or derived from, ants; as, formic acid; in an extended sense, pertaining to, or derived from, formic acid; as, formic ether.

Formica.description: A Linnaean genus of hymenopterous insects, including the common ants. See Ant.

Formidable.description: Exciting fear or apprehension; impressing dread; adapted to excite fear and deter from approach, encounter, or undertaking; alarming.

Formulate.description: To reduce to, or express in, a formula; to put in a clear and definite form of statement or expression.

Formulation.description: The act, process, or result of formulating or reducing to a formula.

Fort.description: A strong or fortified place; usually, a small fortified place, occupied only by troops, surrounded with a ditch, rampart, and parapet, or with palisades, stockades, or other means of defense; a fortification.

Forte.description: The strong point; that in which one excels.

Fortify.description: To add strength to; to strengthen; to confirm; to furnish with power to resist attack.

Forty.description: Four times ten; thirty-nine and one more.

Forum.description: A market place or public place in Rome, where causes were judicially tried, and orations delivered to the people.

Foxglove.description: Any plant of the genus Digitalis. The common English foxglove (Digitalis purpurea) is a handsome perennial or biennial plant, whose leaves are used as a powerful medicine, both as a sedative and diuretic. See Digitalis.

Foxhound.description: One of a special breed of hounds used for chasing foxes.

Foxtail.description: The tail or brush of a fox.

Fracas.description: An uproar; a noisy quarrel; a disturbance; a brawl.

Fragility.description: The condition or quality of being fragile; brittleness; frangibility.

Fragment.description: A part broken off; a small, detached portion; an imperfect part; as, a fragment of an ancient writing.

Fragmentary.description: Composed of fragments, or broken pieces; disconnected; not complete or entire.

Fragrant.description: Affecting the olfactory nerves agreeably; sweet of smell; odorous; having or emitting an agreeable perfume.

Franc.description: A silver coin of France, and since 1795 the unit of the French monetary system. It has been adopted by Belgium and Swizerland. It is equivalent to about nineteen cents, or ten pence, and is divided into 100 centimes.

Franciscan.description: Belonging to the Order of St. Francis of the Franciscans.

Franklin.description: An English freeholder, or substantial householder.

Frantic.description: Mad; raving; furious; violent; wild and disorderly; distracted.

Frap.description: To draw together; to bind with a view to secure and strengthen, as a vessel by passing cables around it; to tighten; as a tackle by drawing the lines together.

Fred.description: Peace; -- a word used in composition, especially in proper names; as, Alfred; Frederic.

Frenzy.description: Any violent agitation of the mind approaching to distraction; violent and temporary derangement of the mental faculties; madness; rage.

Frequency.description: The condition of returning frequently; occurrence often repeated; common occurence; as, the frequency of crimes; the frequency of miracles.

Frequent.description: Often to be met with; happening at short intervals; often repeated or occurring; as, frequent visits.

Frequently.description: At frequent or short intervals; many times; often; repeatedly; commonly.

Fresco.description: A cool, refreshing state of the air; duskiness; coolness; shade.

Fretful.description: Disposed to fret; ill-humored; peevish; angry; in a state of vexation; as, a fretful temper.

Frigid.description: Cold; wanting heat or warmth; of low temperature; as, a frigid climate.

Frist.description: To sell upon credit, as goods.

Frivolity.description: The condition or quality of being frivolous; also, acts or habits of trifling; unbecoming levity of disposition.

Frog.description: An amphibious animal of the genus Rana and related genera, of many species. Frogs swim rapidly, and take long leaps on land. Many of the species utter loud notes in the springtime.

Frolic.description: Full of levity; dancing, playing, or frisking about; full of pranks; frolicsome; gay; merry.

From.description: Out of the neighborhood of; lessening or losing proximity to; leaving behind; by reason of; out of; by aid of; -- used whenever departure, setting out, commencement of action, being, state, occurrence, etc., or procedure, emanation, absence, separation, etc., are to be expressed. It is construed with, and indicates, the point of space or time at which the action, state, etc., are regarded as setting out or beginning; also, less frequently, the source, the cause, the occasion, out of which anything proceeds; -- the aritithesis and correlative of to; as, it, is one hundred miles from Boston to Springfield; he took his sword from his side; light proceeds from the sun; separate the coarse wool from the fine; men have all sprung from Adam, and often go from good to bad, and from bad to worse; the merit of an action depends on the principle from which it proceeds; men judge of facts from personal knowledge, or from testimony.

Frond.description: The organ formed by the combination or union into one body of stem and leaf, and often bearing the fructification; as, the frond of a fern or of a lichen or seaweed; also, the peculiar leaf of a palm tree.

Front.description: The forehead or brow, the part of the face above the eyes; sometimes, also, the whole face.

Frontal.description: Belonging to the front part; being in front

Frost.description: The act of freezing; -- applied chiefly to the congelation of water; congelation of fluids.

Frosted.description: Covered with hoarfrost or anything resembling hoarfrost; ornamented with frosting; also, frost-bitten; as, a frosted cake; frosted glass.

Frosty.description: Attended with, or producing, frost; having power to congeal water; cold; freezing; as, a frosty night.

Frugal.description: Economical in the use or appropriation of resources; not wasteful or lavish; wise in the expenditure or application of force, materials, time, etc.; characterized by frugality; sparing; economical; saving; as, a frugal housekeeper; frugal of time.

Frugality.description: The quality of being frugal; prudent economy; that careful management of anything valuable which expends nothing unnecessarily, and applies what is used to a profitable purpose; thrift; --- opposed to extravagance.

Frump.description: To insult; to flout; to mock; to snub.

Fuchs.description: A student of the first year.

Fugitive.description: Fleeing from pursuit, danger, restraint, etc., escaping, from service, duty etc.; as, a fugitive solder; a fugitive slave; a fugitive debtor.

Fumble.description: To feel or grope about; to make awkward attempts to do or find something.

Fume.description: Exhalation; volatile matter (esp. noxious vapor or smoke) ascending in a dense body; smoke; vapor; reek; as, the fumes of tobacco.

Fumigate.description: To apply smoke to; to expose to smoke or vapor; to purify, or free from infection, by the use of smoke or vapors.

Fumigation.description: The act of fumigating, or applying smoke or vapor, as for disinfection.

Fund.description: An aggregation or deposit of resources from which supplies are or may be drawn for carrying on any work, or for maintaining existence.

Fundamental.description: Pertaining to the foundation or basis; serving for the foundation. Hence: Essential, as an element, principle, or law; important; original; elementary; as, a fundamental truth; a fundamental axiom.

Funeral.description: The solemn rites used in the disposition of a dead human body, whether such disposition be by interment, burning, or otherwise; esp., the ceremony or solemnization of interment; obsequies; burial; -- formerly used in the plural.

Fungus.description: Any one of the Fungi, a large and very complex group of thallophytes of low organization, -- the molds, mildews, rusts, smuts, mushrooms, toadstools, puff balls, and the allies of each.

Funky.description: Pertaining to, or characterized by, great fear, or funking.

Furious.description: Transported with passion or fury; raging; violent; as, a furious animal.

Fuse.description: To liquefy by heat; to render fiuid; to dissolve; to melt.

Fusion.description: The act or operation of melting or rendering fluid by heat; the act of melting together; as, the fusion of metals.

Futurist.description: One whose chief interests are in what is to come; one who anxiously, eagerly, or confidently looks forward to the future; an expectant.

Gabel.description: A rent, service, tribute, custom, tax, impost, or duty; an excise.

Gaby.description: A simpleton; a dunce; a lout.

Gadfly.description: Any dipterous insect of the genus Oestrus, and allied genera of botflies.

Galactic.description: Of or pertaining to milk; got from milk; as, galactic acid.

Galea.description: The upper lip or helmet-shaped part of a labiate flower.

Galena.description: A remedy or antidose for poison; theriaca.

Galilean.description: Of or pertaining to Galileo; as, the Galilean telescope. See Telescope.

Galvanic.description: Of or pertaining to, or exhibiting the phenomena of, galvanism; employing or producing electrical currents.

Gambit.description: A mode of opening the game, in which a pawn is sacrificed to gain an attacking position.

Gamble.description: To play or game for money or other stake.

Gambrel.description: The hind leg of a horse.

Ganglionic.description: Pertaining to, containing, or consisting of, ganglia or ganglion cells; as, a ganglionic artery; the ganglionic columns of the spinal cord.

Gantlet.description: A military punishment formerly in use, wherein the offender was made to run between two files of men facing one another, who struck him as he passed.

Garble.description: To sift or bolt, to separate the fine or valuable parts of from the coarse and useless parts, or from dros or dirt; as, to garble spices.

Garden.description: A piece of ground appropriated to the cultivation of herbs, fruits, flowers, or vegetables.

Gardenia.description: A genus of plants, some species of which produce beautiful and fragrant flowers; Cape jasmine; -- so called in honor of Dr. Alexander Garden.

Gargantuan.description: Characteristic of Gargantua, a gigantic, wonderful personage; enormous; prodigious; inordinate.

Garibaldi.description: A jacket worn by women; -- so called from its resemblance in shape to the red shirt worn by the Italians patriot Garibaldi.

Garlic.description: A plant of the genus Allium (A. sativum is the cultivated variety), having a bulbous root, a very strong smell, and an acrid, pungent taste. Each root is composed of several lesser bulbs, called cloves of garlic, inclosed in a common membranous coat, and easily separable.

Garment.description: Any article of clothing, as a coat, a gown, etc.

Garnet.description: A mineral having many varieties differing in color and in their constituents, but with the same crystallization (isometric), and conforming to the same general chemical formula. The commonest color is red, the luster is vitreous, and the hardness greater than that of quartz. The dodecahedron and trapezohedron are the common forms.

Gascon.description: Of or pertaining to Gascony, in France, or to the Gascons; also, braggart; swaggering.

Gasify.description: To convert into gas, or an aeriform fluid, as by the application of heat, or by chemical processes.

Gasket.description: A line or band used to lash a furled sail securely. Sea gaskets are common lines; harbor gaskets are plaited and decorated lines or bands. Called also casket.

Gasp.description: To open the mouth wide in catching the breath, or in laborious respiration; to labor for breath; to respire convulsively; to pant violently.

Gast.description: To make aghast; to frighten; to terrify. See Aghast.

Gastric.description: Of, pertaining to, or situated near, the stomach; as, the gastric artery.

Gastritis.description: Inflammation of the stomach, esp. of its mucuos membrane.

Gastrointestinal.description: Of or pertaining to the stomach and intestines; gastroenteric.

Gastronomy.description: The art or science of good eating; epicurism; the art of good cheer.

Gastrovascular.description: Having the structure, or performing the functions, both of digestive and circulatory organs; as, the gastrovascular cavity of c/lenterates.

Gemini.description: A constellation of the zodiac, containing the two bright stars Castor and Pollux; also, the third sign of the zodiac, which the sun enters about May 20th.

Gemsbok.description: A South African antelope (Oryx Capensis), having long, sharp, nearly straight horns.

Gena.description: The cheek; the feathered side of the under mandible of a bird.

Genealogy.description: An account or history of the descent of a person or family from an ancestor; enumeration of ancestors and their children in the natural order of succession; a pedigree.

Genesis.description: The act of producing, or giving birth or origin to anything; the process or mode of originating; production; formation; origination.

Geniality.description: The quality of being genial; sympathetic cheerfulness; warmth of disposition and manners.

Genital.description: Pertaining to generation, or to the generative organs.

Genitals.description: The organs of generation; the sexual organs; the private parts.

Genius.description: A good or evil spirit, or demon, supposed by the ancients to preside over a man's destiny in life; a tutelary deity; a supernatural being; a spirit, good or bad.  Cf. Jinnee.

Genre.description: A style of painting, sculpture, or other imitative art, which illustrates everyday life and manners.

Gens.description: A clan or family connection, embracing several families of the same stock, who had a common name and certain common religious rites; a subdivision of the Roman curia or tribe.

Gentle.description: Well-born; of a good family or respectable birth, though not noble.

Gentleman.description: A man well born; one of good family; one above the condition of a yeoman.

Gentlemanly.description: Of, pertaining to, resembling, or becoming, a gentleman; well-behaved; courteous; polite.

Gentlewoman.description: A woman of good family or of good breeding; a woman above the vulgar.

Genus.description: A class of objects divided into several subordinate species; a class more extensive than a species; a precisely defined and exactly divided class; one of the five predicable conceptions, or sorts of terms.

Geodesy.description: That branch of applied mathematics which determines, by means of observations and measurements, the figures and areas of large portions of the earth's surface, or the general figure and dimenshions of the earth; or that branch of surveying in which the curvature of the earth is taken into account, as in the surveys of States, or of long lines of coast.

Geological.description: Of or pertaining to geology, or the science of the earth.

Geologist.description: One versed in the science of geology.

Geology.description: The science which treats: (a) Of the structure and mineral constitution of the globe; structural geology. (b) Of its history as regards rocks, minerals, rivers, valleys, mountains, climates, life, etc.; historical geology. (c) Of the causes and methods by which its structure, features, changes, and conditions have been produced; dynamical geology. See Chart of The Geological Series.

Geometrical.description: Pertaining to, or according to the rules or principles of, geometry; determined by geometry; as, a geometrical solution of a problem.

Geometry.description: That branch of mathematics which investigates the relations, properties, and measurement of solids, surfaces, lines, and angles; the science which treats of the properties and relations of magnitudes; the science of the relations of space.

Giant.description: A man of extraordinari bulk and stature.

Giblet.description: Made of giblets; as, a giblet pie.

Gift.description: Anything given; anything voluntarily transferred by one person to another without compensation; a present; an offering.

Gigantic.description: Of extraordinary size; like a giant.

Gild.description: To overlay with a thin covering of gold; to cover with a golden color; to cause to look like gold.

Glacis.description: A gentle slope, or a smooth, gently sloping bank; especially (Fort.), that slope of earth which inclines from the covered way toward the exterior ground or country (see Illust. of Ravelin).

Glad.description: Pleased; joyous; happy; cheerful; gratified; -- opposed to sorry, sorrowful, or unhappy; -- said of persons, and often followed by of, at, that, or by the infinitive, and sometimes by with, introducing the cause or reason.

Gladiolus.description: A genus of plants having bulbous roots and gladiate leaves, and including many species, some of which are cultivated and valued for the beauty of their flowers; the corn flag; the sword lily.

Gland.description: An organ for secreting something to be used in, or eliminated from, the body; as, the sebaceous glands of the skin; the salivary glands of the mouth.

Glen.description: A secluded and narrow valley; a dale; a depression between hills.

Glib.description: Smooth; slippery; as, ice is glib.

Glibly.description: In a glib manner; as, to speak glibly.

Globular.description: Globe-shaped; having the form of a ball or sphere; spherical, or nearly so; as, globular atoms.

Gloria.description: A doxology (beginning Gloria Patri, Glory be to the Father), sung or said at the end of the Psalms in the service of the Roman Catholic and other churches.

Glorify.description: To make glorious by bestowing glory upon; to confer honor and distinction upon; to elevate to power or happiness, or to celestial glory.

Glory.description: Praise, honor, admiration, or distinction, accorded by common consent to a person or thing; high reputation; honorable fame; renown.

Glumly.description: In a glum manner; sullenly; moodily.

Glut.description: To swallow, or to swallow greedlly; to gorge.

Glutaric.description: Of, pertaining to, or designating, an acid so called; as, glutaric ethers.

Gluten.description: The viscid, tenacious substance which gives adhesiveness to dough.

Glycogen.description: A white, amorphous, tasteless substance resembling starch, soluble in water to an opalescent fluid. It is found abundantly in the liver of most animals, and in small quantity in other organs and tissues, particularly in the embryo. It is quickly changed into sugar when boiled with dilute sulphuric or hydrochloric acid, and also by the action of amylolytic ferments.

Glycol.description: A thick, colorless liquid, C2H4(OH)2, of a sweetish taste, produced artificially from certain ethylene compounds. It is a diacid alcohol, intermediate between ordinary ethyl alcohol and glycerin.

Glycolic.description: Pertaining to, or derived from, glycol; as, glycolic ether; glycolic acid.

Gnosticism.description: The system of philosophy taught by the Gnostics.

Goblet.description: A kind of cup or drinking vessel having a foot or standard, but without a handle.

Goblin.description: An evil or mischievous spirit; a playful or malicious elf; a frightful phantom; a gnome.

Godly.description: Pious; reverencing God, and his character and laws; obedient to the commands of God from love for, and reverence of, his character; conformed to God's law; devout; righteous; as, a godly life.

Godsend.description: Something sent by God; an unexpected acquisiton or piece of good fortune.

Goldcrest.description: The European golden-crested kinglet (Regulus cristatus, or R. regulus); -- called also golden-crested wren, and golden wren. The name is also sometimes applied to the American golden-crested kinglet. See Kinglet.

Golden.description: Made of gold; consisting of gold.

Golf.description: A game played with a small ball and a bat or club crooked at the lower end. He who drives the ball into each of a series of small holes in the ground and brings it into the last hole with the fewest strokes is the winner.

Gonad.description: One of the masses of generative tissue primitively alike in both sexes, but giving rise to either an ovary or a testis; a generative gland; a germ gland.

Gondola.description: A long, narrow boat with a high prow and stern, used in the canals of Venice. A gondola is usually propelled by one or two oarsmen who stand facing the prow, or by poling. A gondola for passengers has a small open cabin amidships, for their protection against the sun or rain. A sumptuary law of Venice required that gondolas should be painted black, and they are customarily so painted now.

Goral.description: An Indian goat antelope (Nemorhedus goral), resembling the chamois.

Gordian.description: Pertaining to Gordius, king of Phrygia, or to a knot tied by him; hence, intricate; complicated; inextricable.

Gorgon.description: One of three fabled sisters, Stheno, Euryale, and Medusa, with snaky hair and of terrific aspect, the sight of whom turned the beholder to stone. The name is particularly given to Medusa.

Gorgonian.description: Pertaining to, or resembling, a Gorgon; terrifying into stone; terrific.

Gory.description: Covered with gore or clotted blood.

Gospel.description: Glad tidings; especially, the good news concerning Christ, the Kingdom of God, and salvation.

Grab.description: A vessel used on the Malabar coast, having two or three masts.

Gradient.description: Moving by steps; walking; as, gradient automata.

Gradual.description: Proceeding by steps or degrees; advancing, step by step, as in ascent or descent or from one state to another; regularly progressive; slow; as, a gradual increase of knowledge; a gradual decline.

Graduate.description: To mark with degrees; to divide into regular steps, grades, or intervals, as the scale of a thermometer, a scheme of punishment or rewards, etc.

Gradus.description: A dictionary of prosody, designed as an aid in writing Greek or Latin poetry.

Graf.description: A German title of nobility, equivalent to earl in English, or count in French. See Earl.

Graft.description: A small shoot or scion of a tree inserted in another tree, the stock of which is to support and nourish it. The two unite and become one tree, but the graft determines the kind of fruit.

Grand.description: Of large size or extent; great; extensive; hence, relatively great; greatest; chief; principal; as, a grand mountain; a grand army; a grand mistake.

Grandiloquent.description: Speaking in a lofty style; pompous; bombastic.

Granitic.description: Like granite in composition, color, etc.; having the nature of granite; as, granitic texture.

Grant.description: To give over; to make conveyance of; to give the possession or title of; to convey; -- usually in answer to petition.

Granular.description: Consisting of, or resembling, grains; as, a granular substance.

Granulation.description: The act or process of forming or crystallizing into grains; as, the granulation of powder and sugar.

Granule.description: A little grain a small particle; a pellet.

Grasp.description: To seize and hold by clasping or embracing with the fingers or arms; to catch to take possession of.

Gratify.description: To please; to give pleasure to; to satisfy; to soothe; to indulge; as, to gratify the taste, the appetite, the senses, the desires, the mind, etc.

Gratis.description: For nothing; without fee or recompense; freely; gratuitously.

Gratuity.description: Something given freely or without recompense; a free gift; a present.

Gravel.description: Small stones, or fragments of stone; very small pebbles, often intermixed with particles of sand.

Gravimetric.description: Of or pertaining to measurement by weight; measured by weight.

Gravity.description: The state of having weight; beaviness; as, the gravity of lead.

Gravy.description: The juice or other liquid matter that drips from flesh in cooking, made into a dressing for the food when served up.

Grego.description: A short jacket or cloak, made of very thick, coarse cloth, with a hood attached, worn by the Greeks and others in the Levant.

Gregorian.description: Pertaining to, or originated by, some person named Gregory, especially one of the popes of that name.

Grid.description: A grating of thin parallel bars, similar to a gridiron.

Grim.description: Of forbidding or fear-inspiring aspect; fierce; stern; surly; cruel; frightful; horrible.

Grimy.description: Full of grime; begrimed; dirty; foul.

Grind.description: To reduce to powder by friction, as in a mill, or with the teeth; to crush into small fragments; to produce as by the action of millstones.

Grindle.description: The bowfin; -- called also Johnny Grindle.

Grisly.description: Frightful; horrible; dreadful; harsh; as, grisly locks; a grisly specter.

Grist.description: Ground corn; that which is ground at one time; as much grain as is carried to the mill at one time, or the meal it produces.

Grit.description: Sand or gravel; rough, hard particles.

Grog.description: A mixture of spirit and water not sweetened; hence, any intoxicating liquor.

Gros.description: A heavy silk with a dull finish; as, gros de Naples; gros de Tours.

Grovel.description: To creep on the earth, or with the face to the ground; to lie prone, or move uneasily with the body prostrate on the earth; to lie fiat on one's belly, expressive of abjectness; to crawl.

Grub.description: To dig in or under the ground, generally for an object that is difficult to reach or extricate; to be occupied in digging.

Gruel.description: A light, liquid food, made by boiling meal of maize, oatmeal, or fiour in water or milk; thin porridge.

Grum.description: Morose; severe of countenance; sour; surly; glum; grim.

Grumble.description: To murmur or mutter with discontent; to make ill-natured complaints in a low voice and a surly manner.

Grunt.description: To make a deep, short noise, as a hog; to utter a short groan or a deep guttural sound.

Guanaco.description: A South American mammal (Auchenia huanaco), allied to the llama, but of larger size and more graceful form, inhabiting the southern Andes and Patagonia. It is supposed by some to be the llama in a wild state.

Guano.description: A substance found in great abundance on some coasts or islands frequented by sea fowls, and composed chiefly of their excrement. It is rich in phosphates and ammonia, and is used as a powerful fertilizer.

Guava.description: A tropical tree, or its fruit, of the genus Psidium. Two varieties are well known, the P. pyriferum, or white guava, and P. pomiferum, or red guava.  The fruit or berry is shaped like a pomegranate, but is much smaller. It is somewhat astringent, but makes a delicious jelly.

Gulf.description: A hollow place in the earth; an abyss; a deep chasm or basin,

Gulp.description: To swallow eagerly, or in large draughts; to swallow up; to take down at one swallow.

Gumbo.description: A soup thickened with the mucilaginous pods of the okra; okra soup.

Gunflint.description: A sharpened flint for the lock of a gun, to ignite the charge. It was in common use before the introduction of percussion caps.

Guru.description: A spiritual teacher, guide, or confessor amoung the Hindoos.

Gust.description: A sudden squall; a violent blast of wind; a sudden and brief rushing or driving of the wind. Snow, and hail, stormy gust and flaw.

Gusto.description: Nice or keen appreciation or enjoyment; relish; taste; fancy.

Gusty.description: Subject to, or characterized by, gusts or squalls; windy; stormy; tempestuous.

Gymnasium.description: A place or building where athletic exercises are performed; a school for gymnastics.

Gymnast.description: One who teaches or practices gymnastic exercises; the manager of a gymnasium; an athlete.

Gymnastics.description: Athletic or disciplinary exercises; the art of performing gymnastic exercises; also, disciplinary exercises for the intellect or character.

Gynecology.description: The science which treats of the structure and diseases of women.

Gypsum.description: A mineral consisting of the hydrous sulphate of lime (calcium). When calcined, it forms plaster of Paris. Selenite is a transparent, crystalline variety; alabaster, a fine, white, massive variety.

Gypsy.description: One of a vagabond race, whose tribes, coming originally from India, entered Europe in 14th or 15th centry, and are now scattered over Turkey, Russia, Hungary, Spain, England, etc., living by theft, fortune telling, horsejockeying, tinkering, etc.  Cf. Bohemian, Romany.

Gyroscopic.description: Pertaining to the gyroscope; resembling the motion of the gyroscope.

Habit.description: The usual condition or state of a person or thing, either natural or acquired, regarded as something had, possessed, and firmly retained; as, a religious habit; his habit is morose; elms have a spreading habit; esp., physical temperament or constitution; as, a full habit of body.

Habitable.description: Capable of being inhabited; that may be inhabited or dwelt in; as, the habitable world.

Habitat.description: The natural abode, locality or region of an animal or plant.

Habitual.description: Formed or acquired by habit or use.

Hacienda.description: A large estate where work of any kind is done, as agriculture, manufacturing, mining, or raising of animals; a cultivated farm, with a good house, in distinction from a farming establishment with rude huts for herdsmen, etc.; -- a word used in Spanish-American regions.

Hades.description: The nether world (according to classical mythology, the abode of the shades, ruled over by Hades or Pluto); the invisible world; the grave.

Haft.description: A handle; that part of an instrument or vessel taken into the hand, and by which it is held and used; -- said chiefly of a knife, sword, or dagger; the hilt.

Hakim.description: A wise man; a physician, esp. a Mohammedan.

Halcyon.description: A kingfisher. By modern ornithologists restricted to a genus including a limited number of species having omnivorous habits, as the sacred kingfisher (Halcyon sancta) of Australia.

Halibut.description: A large, northern, marine flatfish (Hippoglossus vulgaris), of the family Pleuronectidae. It often grows very large, weighing more than three hundred pounds. It is an important food fish.

Halo.description: A luminous circle, usually prismatically colored, round the sun or moon, and supposed to be caused by the refraction of light through crystals of ice in the atmosphere. Connected with halos there are often white bands, crosses, or arches, resulting from the same atmospheric conditions.

Halogen.description: An electro-negative element or radical, which, by combination with a metal, forms a haloid salt; especially, chlorine, bromine, and iodine; sometimes, also, fluorine and cyanogen. See Chlorine family, under Chlorine.

Halt.description: 3d pers. sing. pres. of Hold, contraction for holdeth.

Hamlet.description: A small village; a little cluster of houses in the country.

Hand.description: That part of the fore limb below the forearm or wrist in man and monkeys, and the corresponding part in many other animals; manus; paw. See Manus.

Handful.description: As much as the hand will grasp or contain.

Handicap.description: An allowance of a certain amount of time or distance in starting, granted in a race to the competitor possessing inferior advantages; or an additional weight or other hindrance imposed upon the one possessing superior advantages, in order to equalize, as much as possible, the chances of success; as, the handicap was five seconds, or ten pounds, and the like.

Handicraft.description: A trade requiring skill of hand; manual occupation; handcraft.

Handily.description: In a handy manner; skillfully; conveniently.

Handle.description: To touch; to feel with the hand; to use or hold with the hand.

Hank.description: A parcel consisting of two or more skeins of yarn or thread tied together.

Hanoverian.description: Of or pertaining to Hanover or its people, or to the House of Hanover in England.

Hanseatic.description: Pertaining to the Hanse towns, or to their confederacy.

Hard.description: Not easily penetrated, cut, or separated into parts; not yielding to pressure; firm; solid; compact; -- applied to material bodies, and opposed to soft; as, hard wood; hard flesh; a hard apple.

Harden.description: To make hard or harder; to make firm or compact; to indurate; as, to harden clay or iron.

Hardly.description: In a hard or difficult manner; with difficulty.

Hards.description: The refuse or coarse part of fiax; tow.

Hardy.description: Bold; brave; stout; daring; resolu?e; intrepid.

Harem.description: The apartments or portion of the house allotted to females in Mohammedan families.

Harl.description: A filamentous substance; especially, the filaments of flax or hemp.

Harlequin.description: A buffoon, dressed in party-colored clothes, who plays tricks, often without speaking, to divert the bystanders or an audience; a merry-andrew; originally, a droll rogue of Italian comedy.

Harlot.description: A churl; a common man; a person, male or female, of low birth.

Harmel.description: A kind of rue (Ruta sylvestris) growing in India. At Lahore the seeds are used medicinally and for fumigation.

Harmful.description: Full of harm; injurious; hurtful; mischievous.

Harmonica.description: A musical instrument, consisting of a series of hemispherical glasses which, by touching the edges with the dampened finger, give forth the tones.

Harmonics.description: The doctrine or science of musical sounds.

Harmonium.description: A musical instrument, resembling a small organ and especially designed for church music, in which the tones are produced by forcing air by means of a bellows so as to cause the vibration of free metallic reeds. It is now made with one or two keyboards, and has pedals and stops.

Harmony.description: The just adaptation of parts to each other, in any system or combination of things, or in things, or things intended to form a connected whole; such an agreement between the different parts of a design or composition as to produce unity of effect; as, the harmony of the universe.

Harp.description: A musical instrument consisting of a triangular frame furnished with strings and sometimes with pedals, held upright, and played with the fingers.

Harpist.description: A player on the harp; a harper.

Hart.description: A stag; the male of the red deer. See the Note under Buck.

Harten.description: To hearten; to encourage; to incite.

Hartshorn.description: The horn or antler of the hart, or male red deer.

Harvest.description: The gathering of a crop of any kind; the ingathering of the crops; also, the season of gathering grain and fruits, late summer or early autumn.

Hast.description: 2d pers. sing. pres. of. Have, contr. of havest.

Hastily.description: In haste; with speed or quickness; speedily; nimbly.

Hasty.description: Involving haste; done, made, etc., in haste; as, a hasty sketch.

Hatred.description: Strong aversion; intense dislike; hate; an affection of the mind awakened by something regarded as evil.

Havana.description: Of or pertaining to Havana, the capital of the island of Cuba; as, an Havana cigar

Haven.description: A bay, recess, or inlet of the sea, or the mouth of a river, which affords anchorage and shelter for shipping; a harbor; a port.

Havoc.description: Wide and general destruction; devastation; waste.

Hazel.description: A shrub or small tree of the genus Corylus, as the C. avellana, bearing a nut containing a kernel of a mild, farinaceous taste; the filbert. The American species are C. Americana, which produces the common hazelnut, and C. rostrata. See Filbert.

Hazy.description: Thick with haze; somewhat obscured with haze; not clear or transparent.

Hectic.description: Habitual; constitutional; pertaining especially to slow waste of animal tissue, as in consumption; as, a hectic type in disease; a hectic flush.

Hegemony.description: Leadership; preponderant influence or authority; -- usually applied to the relation of a government or state to its neighbors or confederates.

Helena.description: See St. Elmo's fire, under Saint.

Helical.description: Of or pertaining to, or in the form of, a helix; spiral; as, a helical staircase; a helical spring.

Helicon.description: A mountain in Boeotia, in Greece, supposed by the Greeks to be the residence of Apollo and the Muses.

Helium.description: A gaseous element found in the atmospheres of the sun and earth and in some rare minerals.

Hellenism.description: A phrase or form of speech in accordance with genius and construction or idioms of the Greek language; a Grecism.

Helmet.description: A defensive covering for the head. See Casque, Headpiece, Morion, Sallet, and Illust. of Beaver.

Helmeted.description: Wearing a helmet; furnished with or having a helmet or helmet-shaped part; galeate.

Helmsman.description: The man at the helm; a steersman.

Helot.description: A slave in ancient Sparta; a Spartan serf; hence, a slave or serf.

Help.description: To furnish with strength or means for the successful performance of any action or the attainment of any object; to aid; to assist; as, to help a man in his work; to help one to remember; -- the following infinitive is commonly used without to; as, "Help me scale yon balcony."

Helpful.description: Furnishing help; giving aid; assistant; useful; salutary.

Hematology.description: The science which treats of the blood.

Hemiplegia.description: A palsy that affects one side only of the body.

Hemoglobin.description: The normal coloring matter of the red blood corpuscles of vertebrate animals. It is composed of hematin and globulin, and is also called haematoglobulin. In arterial blood, it is always combined with oxygen, and is then called oxyhemoglobin. It crystallizes under different forms from different animals, and when crystallized, is called haematocrystallin. See Blood crystal, under Blood.

Hemp.description: A plant of the genus Cannabis (C. sativa), the fibrous skin or bark of which is used for making cloth and cordage. The name is also applied to various other plants yielding fiber.

Hempen.description: Made of hemp; as, a hempen cord.

Henry.description: The unit of electric induction; the induction in a circuit when the electro-motive force induced in this circuit is one volt, while the inducing current varies at the rate of one ampere a second.

Hepatic.description: Of or pertaining to the liver; as, hepatic artery; hepatic diseases.

Herald.description: An officer whose business was to denounce or proclaim war, to challenge to battle, to proclaim peace, and to bear messages from the commander of an army. He was invested with a sacred and inviolable character.

Heraldic.description: Of or pertaining to heralds or heraldry; as, heraldic blazoning; heraldic language.

Heraldry.description: The art or office of a herald; the art, practice, or science of recording genealogies, and blazoning arms or ensigns armorial; also, of marshaling cavalcades, processions, and public ceremonies.

Herculean.description: Requiring the strength of Hercules; hence, very great, difficult, or dangerous; as, an Herculean task.
