Hercules.description: A hero, fabled to have been the son of Jupiter and Alcmena, and celebrated for great strength, esp. for the accomplishment of his twelve great tasks or "labors."

Heresy.description: An opinion held in opposition to the established or commonly received doctrine, and tending to promote a division or party, as in politics, literature, philosophy, etc.; -- usually, but not necessarily, said in reproach.

Heretic.description: One who holds to a heresy; one who believes some doctrine contrary to the established faith or prevailing religion.

Heritable.description: Capable of being inherited or of passing by inheritance; inheritable.

Hero.description: An illustrious man, supposed to be exalted, after death, to a place among the gods; a demigod, as Hercules.

Heroic.description: Of or pertaining to, or like, a hero; of the nature of heroes; distinguished by the existence of heroes; as, the heroic age; an heroic people; heroic valor.

Heron.description: Any wading bird of the genus Ardea and allied genera, of the family Ardeidae. The herons have a long, sharp bill, and long legs and toes, with the claw of the middle toe toothed. The common European heron (Ardea cinerea) is remarkable for its directly ascending flight, and was formerly hunted with the larger falcons.

Hesitancy.description: The act of hesitating, or pausing to consider; slowness in deciding; vacillation; also, the manner of one who hesitates.

Hesitant.description: Not prompt in deciding or acting; hesitating.

Heterodox.description: Contrary to, or differing from, some acknowledged standard, as the Bible, the creed of a church, the decree of a council, and the like; not orthodox; heretical; -- said of opinions, doctrines, books, etc., esp. upon theological subjects.

Heterodoxy.description: An opinion or doctrine, or a system of doctrines, contrary to some established standard of faith, as the Scriptures, the creed or standards of a church, etc.; heresy.

Hetman.description: A Cossack headman or general. The title of chief hetman is now held by the heir to the throne of Russia.

Heuristic.description: Serving to discover or find out.

Hexane.description: Any one of five hydrocarbons, C6H14, of the paraffin series. They are colorless, volatile liquids, and are so called because the molecule has six carbon atoms.

Hidalgo.description: A title, denoting a Spanish nobleman of the lower class.

Hilt.description: A handle; especially, the handle of a sword, dagger, or the like.

Himself.description: An emphasized form of the third person masculine pronoun; -- used as a subject usually with he; as, he himself will bear the blame; used alone in the predicate, either in the nominative or objective case; as, it is himself who saved himself.

Hind.description: The female of the red deer, of which the male is the stag.

Hindi.description: The name given by Europeans to that form of the Hindustani language which is chiefly spoken by native Hindoos. In employs the Devanagari character, in which Sanskrit is written.

Hindu.description: A native inhabitant of Hindostan. As an ethnical term it is confined to the Dravidian and Aryan races; as a religious name it is restricted to followers of the Veda.

Hint.description: To bring to mind by a slight mention or remote allusion; to suggest in an indirect manner; as, to hint a suspicion.

Hispanic.description: Of or pertaining to Spain or its language; as, Hispanic words.

Histology.description: That branch of biological science, which treats of the minute (microscopic) structure of animal and vegetable tissues; -- called also histiology.

Historian.description: A writer of history; a chronicler; an annalist.

Historical.description: Of or pertaining to history, or the record of past events; as, an historical poem; the historic page.

Hoax.description: A deception for mockery or mischief; a deceptive trick or story; a practical joke.

Hobnob.description: Have or have not; -- a familiar invitation to reciprocal drinking.

Hold.description: The whole interior portion of a vessel below the lower deck, in which the cargo is stowed.

Holmium.description: A rare element said to be contained in gadolinite.

Holt.description: 3d pers. sing. pres. of Hold, contr. from holdeth.

Holy.description: Set apart to the service or worship of God; hallowed; sacred; reserved from profane or common use; holy vessels; a holy priesthood.

Homeric.description: Of or pertaining to Homer, the most famous of Greek poets; resembling the poetry of Homer.

Homicidal.description: Pertaining to homicide; tending to homicide; murderous.

Homily.description: A discourse or sermon read or pronounced to an audience; a serious discourse.

Hominy.description: Maize hulled and broken, and prepared for food by being boiled in water.

Homonym.description: A word having the same sound as another, but differing from it in meaning; as the noun bear and the verb bear.

Honk.description: The cry of a wild goose.

Horizontal.description: Pertaining to, or near, the horizon.

Horn.description: A hard, projecting, and usually pointed organ, growing upon the heads of certain animals, esp. of the ruminants, as cattle, goats, and the like. The hollow horns of the Ox family consist externally of true horn, and are never shed.

Hornet.description: A large, strong wasp. The European species (Vespa crabro) is of a dark brown and yellow color. It is very pugnacious, and its sting is very severe. Its nest is constructed of a paperlike material, and the layers of comb are hung together by columns. The American white-faced hornet (V. maculata) is larger and has similar habits.

Hospitable.description: Receiving and entertaining strangers or guests with kindness and without reward; kind to strangers and guests; characterized by hospitality.

Hospital.description: A place for shelter or entertainment; an inn.

Hospitality.description: The act or practice of one who is hospitable; reception and entertainment of strangers or guests without reward, or with kind and generous liberality.

Host.description: The consecrated wafer, believed to be the body of Christ, which in the Mass is offered as a sacrifice; also, the bread before consecration.

Hostility.description: State of being hostile; public or private enemy; unfriendliness; animosity.

Hotbed.description: A bed of earth heated by fermenting manure or other substances, and covered with glass, intended for raising early plants, or for nourishing exotics.

Hotel.description: A house for entertaining strangers or travelers; an inn or public house, of the better class.

Hotly.description: In a hot or fiery manner; ardently; vehemently; violently; hastily; as, a hotly pursued.

Hovel.description: An open shed for sheltering cattle, or protecting produce, etc., from the weather.

Hued.description: Having color; -- usually in composition; as, bright-hued; many-hued.

Huge.description: Very large; enormous; immense; excessive; -- used esp. of material bulk, but often of qualities, extent, etc.; as, a huge ox; a huge space; a huge difference.

Huguenot.description: A French Protestant of the period of the religious wars in France in the 16th century.

Hulk.description: The body of a ship or decked vessel of any kind; esp., the body of an old vessel laid by as unfit for service.

Humanize.description: To render human or humane; to soften; to make gentle by overcoming cruel dispositions and rude habits; to refine or civilize.

Humanness.description: The quality or state of being human.

Humble.description: Near the ground; not high or lofty; not pretentious or magnificent; unpretending; unassuming; as, a humble cottage.

Humbler.description: One who, or that which, humbles some one.

Humbug.description: An imposition under fair pretenses; something contrived in order to deceive and mislead; a trick by cajolery; a hoax.

Humerus.description: The bone of the brachium, or upper part of the arm or fore limb.

Humiliate.description: To reduce to a lower position in one's own eyes, or in the eyes of others; to humble; to mortify.

Humiliation.description: The act of humiliating or humbling; abasement of pride; mortification.

Humor.description: Moisture, especially, the moisture or fluid of animal bodies, as the chyle, lymph, etc.; as, the humors of the eye, etc.

Humoral.description: Pertaining to, or proceeding from, the humors; as, a humoral fever.

Humorist.description: One who attributes diseases of the state of the humors.

Hump.description: A protuberance; especially, the protuberance formed by a crooked back.

Hundred.description: The product of ten mulitplied by ten, or the number of ten times ten; a collection or sum, consisting of ten times ten units or objects; five score. Also, a symbol representing one hundred units, as 100 or C.

Hungarian.description: Of or pertaining to Hungary or to the people of Hungary.

Hungry.description: Feeling hunger; having a keen appetite; feeling uneasiness or distress from want of food; hence, having an eager desire.

Hunk.description: A large lump or piece; a hunch; as, a hunk of bread.

Hunks.description: A covetous, sordid man; a miser; a niggard.

Hunt.description: To search for or follow after, as game or wild animals; to chase; to pursue for the purpose of catching or killing; to follow with dogs or guns for sport or exercise; as, to hunt a deer.

Huntsman.description: One who hunts, or who practices hunting.

Husband.description: The male head of a household; one who orders the economy of a family.

Husbandry.description: Care of domestic affairs; economy; domestic management; thrift.

Husk.description: The external covering or envelope of certain fruits or seeds; glume; hull; rind; in the United States, especially applied to the covering of the ears of maize.

Husky.description: Abounding with husks; consisting of husks.

Hybrid.description: The offspring of the union of two distinct species; an animal or plant produced from the mixture of two species. See Mongrel.

Hydra.description: A serpent or monster in the lake or marsh of Lerna, in the Peloponnesus, represented as having many heads, one of which, when cut off, was immediately succeeded by two others, unless the wound was cauterized. It was slain by Hercules. Hence, a terrible monster.

Hydrant.description: A discharge pipe with a valve and spout at which water may be drawn from the mains of waterworks; a water plug.

Hydrocarbon.description: A compound containing only hydrogen and carbon, as methane, benzene, etc.; also, by extension, any of their derivatives.

Hydrogen.description: A gaseous element, colorless, tasteless, and odorless, the lightest known substance, being fourteen and a half times lighter than air (hence its use in filling balloons), and over eleven thousand times lighter than water. It is very abundant, being an ingredient of water and of many other substances, especially those of animal or vegetable origin. It may by produced in many ways, but is chiefly obtained by the action of acids (as sulphuric) on metals, as zinc, iron, etc. It is very inflammable, and is an ingredient of coal gas and water gas. It is standard of chemical equivalents or combining weights, and also of valence, being the typical monad. Symbol H. Atomic weight 1.

Hydroxide.description: A hydrate; a substance containing hydrogen and oxygen, made by combining water with an oxide, and yielding water by elimination. The hydroxides are regarded as compounds of hydroxyl, united usually with basic element or radical; as, calcium hydroxide ethyl hydroxide.

Hyena.description: Any carnivorous mammal of the family Hyaenidae, of which three living species are known. They are large and strong, but cowardly. They feed chiefly on carrion, and are nocturnal in their habits.

Hymen.description: A fold of muscous membrane often found at the orifice of the vagina; the vaginal membrane.

Hymnal.description: A collection of hymns; a hymn book.

Hymnology.description: The hymns or sacred lyrics composed by authors of a particular country or period; as, the hymnology of the eighteenth century; also, the collective body of hymns used by any particular church or religious body; as, the Anglican hymnology.

Hyperion.description: The god of the sun; in the later mythology identified with Apollo, and distinguished for his beauty.

Hypnotic.description: Having the quality of producing sleep; tending to produce sleep; soporific.

Hypocrisy.description: The act or practice of a hypocrite; a feigning to be what one is not, or to feel what one does not feel; a dissimulation, or a concealment of one's real character, disposition, or motives; especially, the assuming of false appearance of virtue or religion; a simulation of goodness.

Hypocritical.description: Of or pertaining to a hypocrite, or to hypocrisy; as, a hypocriticalperson; a hypocritical look; a hypocritical action.

Hyson.description: A fragrant kind of green tea.

Hysteria.description: A nervous affection, occurring almost exclusively in women, in which the emotional and reflex excitability is exaggerated, and the will power correspondingly diminished, so that the patient loses control over the emotions, becomes the victim of imaginary sensations, and often falls into paroxism or fits.

Hysterical.description: Of or pertaining to hysteria; affected, or troubled, with hysterics; convulsive, fitful.

Ibis.description: Any bird of the genus Ibis and several allied genera, of the family Ibidae, inhabiting both the Old World and the New. Numerous species are known. They are large, wading birds, having a long, curved beak, and feed largely on reptiles.

Jacob.description: A Hebrew patriarch (son of Isaac, and ancestor of the Jews), who in a vision saw a ladder reaching up to heaven (Gen. xxviii. 12); -- also called Israel.

Jacobin.description: A Dominican friar; -- so named because, before the French Revolution, that order had a convent in the Rue St. Jacques, Paris.

Jacobus.description: An English gold coin, of the value of twenty-five shillings sterling, struck in the reign of James I.

Jaguar.description: A large and powerful feline animal (Felis onca), ranging from Texas and Mexico to Patagonia. It is usually brownish yellow, with large, dark, somewhat angular rings, each generally inclosing one or two dark spots. It is chiefly arboreal in its habits. Called also the American tiger.

Jainism.description: The heterodox Hindoo religion, of which the most striking features are the exaltation of saints or holy mortals, called jins, above the ordinary Hindoo gods, and the denial of the divine origin and infallibility of the Vedas. It is intermediate between Brahmanism and Buddhism, having some things in common with each.

Jangle.description: To sound harshly or discordantly, as bells out of tune.

Jansenist.description: A follower of Cornelius Jansen, a Roman Catholic bishop of Ypres, in Flanders, in the 17th century, who taught certain doctrines denying free will and the possibility of resisting divine grace.

Janus.description: A Latin deity represented with two faces looking in opposite directions. Numa is said to have dedicated to Janus the covered passage at Rome, near the Forum, which is usually called the Temple of Janus. This passage was open in war and closed in peace.

Japan.description: Work varnished and figured in the Japanese manner; also, the varnish or lacquer used in japanning.

Japonica.description: A species of Camellia (Camellia Japonica), a native of Japan, bearing beautiful red or white flowers. Many other genera have species of the same name.

Jargon.description: Confused, unintelligible language; gibberish; hence, an artificial idiom or dialect; cant language; slang.

Java.description: One of the islands of the Malay Archipelago belonging to the Netherlands.

Javelin.description: A sort of light spear, to be thrown or cast by thew hand; anciently, a weapon of war used by horsemen and foot soldiers; now used chiefly in hunting the wild boar and other fierce game.

Jenkins.description: name of contempt for a flatterer of persons high in social or official life; as, the Jenkins employed by a newspaper.

Jest.description: A deed; an action; a gest.

Jesuit.description: One of a religious order founded by Ignatius Loyola, and approved in 1540, under the title of The Society of Jesus.

Jesus.description: The Savior; the name of the Son of God as announced by the angel to his parents; the personal name of Our Lord, in distinction from Christ, his official appellation.

Jetson.description: Goods which sink when cast into the sea, and remain under water; -- distinguished from flotsam, goods which float, and ligan, goods which are sunk attached to a buoy.

Jilt.description: A woman who capriciously deceives her lover; a coquette; a flirt.

Jingle.description: To sound with a fine, sharp, rattling, clinking, or tinkling sound; as, sleigh bells jingle.

Jocular.description: Given to jesting; jocose; as, a jocular person.

Jolt.description: To shake with short, abrupt risings and fallings, as a carriage moving on rough ground; as, the coach jolts.

Jorden.description: A pot or vessel with a large neck, formerly used by physicians and alchemists.

Jovial.description: Of or pertaining to the god, or the planet, Jupiter.

Jovian.description: Of or pertaining to Jove, or Jupiter (either the deity or the planet).

Jubilant.description: Uttering songs of triumph; shouting with joy; triumphant; exulting.

Judas.description: The disciple who betrayed Christ. Hence: A treacherous person; one who betrays under the semblance of friendship.

Judiciary.description: Of or pertaining to courts of judicature, or legal tribunals; judicial; as, a judiciary proceeding.

Jugular.description: Of or pertaining to the throat or neck; as, the jugular vein.

Julep.description: A refreshing drink flavored with aromatic herbs

Julian.description: Relating to, or derived from, Julius Caesar.

July.description: The seventh month of the year, containing thirty-one days.

Jumble.description: To mix in a confused mass; to put or throw together without order; -- often followed by together or up.

Jump.description: A kind of loose jacket for men.

Junco.description: Any bird of the genus Junco, which includes several species of North American finches; -- called also snowbird, or blue snowbird.

Jungle.description: A dense growth of brushwood, grasses, reeds, vines, etc.; an almost impenetrable thicket of trees, canes, and reedy vegetation, as in India, Africa, Australia, and Brazil.

Junk.description: A fragment of any solid substance; a thick piece. See Chunk.

Junket.description: A cheese cake; a sweetmeat; any delicate food.

Junta.description: A council; a convention; a tribunal; an assembly; esp., the grand council of state in Spain.

Jura.description: 1. A range of mountains between France and Switzerland.

Jurist.description: One who professes the science of law; one versed in the law, especially in the civil law; a writer on civil and international law.

Jury.description: For temporary use; -- applied to a temporary contrivance.

Just.description: Conforming or conformable to rectitude or justice; not doing wrong to any; violating no right or obligation; upright; righteous; honest; true; -- said both of persons and things.

Justifiable.description: Capable of being justified, or shown to be just.

Justify.description: To prove or show to be just; to vindicate; to maintain or defend as conformable to law, right, justice, propriety, or duty.

Justly.description: In a just manner; in conformity to law, justice, or propriety; by right; honestly; fairly; accurately.

Juxtaposition.description: A placing or being placed in nearness or contiguity, or side by side; as, a juxtaposition of words.

Kama.description: The Hindoo Cupid. He is represented as a beautiful youth, with a bow of sugar cane or flowers.

Kansas.description: A tribe of Indians allied to the Winnebagoes and Osages. They formerly inhabited the region which is now the State of Kansas, but were removed to the Indian Territory.

Kantian.description: Of or pertaining to Immanuel Kant, the German philosopher; conformed or relating to any or all of the philosophical doctrines of Immanuel Kant.

Karma.description: One's acts considered as fixing one's lot in the future existence. (Theos.) The doctrine of fate as the inflexible result of cause and effect; the theory of inevitable consequence.

Karn.description: A pile of rocks; sometimes, the solid rock. See Cairn.

Katydid.description: A large, green, arboreal, orthopterous insect (Cyrtophyllus concavus) of the family Locustidae, common in the United States. The males have stridulating organs at the bases of the front wings. During the summer and autumn, in the evening, the males make a peculiar, loud, shrill sound, resembling the combination Katy-did, whence the name.

Kelp.description: The calcined ashes of seaweed, -- formerly much used in the manufacture of glass, now used in the manufacture of iodine.

Kendal.description: A cloth colored green by dye obtained from the woad-waxen, formerly used by Flemish weavers at Kendal, in Westmoreland, England.

Keno.description: A gambling game, a variety of the game of lotto, played with balls or knobs, numbered, and cards also numbered.

Keratin.description: A nitrogenous substance, or mixture of substances, containing sulphur in a loose state of combination, and forming the chemical basis of epidermal tissues, such as horn, hair, feathers, and the like. It is an insoluble substance, and, unlike elastin, is not dissolved even by gastric or pancreatic juice. By decomposition with sulphuric acid it yields leucin and tyrosin, as does albumin. Called also epidermose.

Kidnap.description: To take (any one) by force or fear, and against one's will, with intent to carry to another place.

Kiln.description: A large stove or oven; a furnace of brick or stone, or a heated chamber, for the purpose of hardening, burning, or drying anything; as, a kiln for baking or hardening earthen vessels; a kiln for drying grain, meal, lumber, etc.; a kiln for calcining limestone.

Labrador.description: A region of British America on the Atlantic coast, north of Newfoundland.

Lactic.description: Of or pertaining to milk; procured from sour milk or whey; as, lactic acid; lactic fermentation, etc.

Laden.description: Loaded; freighted; burdened; as, a laden vessel; a laden heart.

Ladino.description: One of the half-breed descendants of whites and Indians; a mestizo; -- so called throughout Central America. They are usually of a yellowish orange tinge.

Ladle.description: A cuplike spoon, often of large size, with a long handle, used in lading or dipping.

Lady.description: A woman who looks after the domestic affairs of a family; a mistress; the female head of a household.

Laity.description: The people, as distinguished from the clergy; the body of the people not in orders.

Lament.description: To express or feel sorrow; to weep or wail; to mourn.

Lamentable.description: Mourning; sorrowful; expressing grief; as, a lamentable countenance.

Lamia.description: A monster capable of assuming a woman's form, who was said to devour human beings or suck their blood; a vampire; a sorceress; a witch.

Lamina.description: A thin plate or scale; a layer or coat lying over another; -- said of thin plates or platelike substances, as of bone or minerals.

Lancet.description: A surgical instrument of various forms, commonly sharp-pointed and two-edged, used in venesection, and in opening abscesses, etc.

Landlady.description: A woman having real estate which she leases to a tenant or tenants.

Landlord.description: The lord of a manor, or of land; the owner of land or houses which he leases to a tenant or tenants.

Landman.description: A man who lives or serves on land; -- opposed to seaman.

Landmark.description: A mark to designate the boundary of land; any , mark or fixed object (as a marked tree, a stone, a ditch, or a heap of stones) by which the limits of a farm, a town, or other portion of territory may be known and preserved.

Landsman.description: One who lives on the land; -- opposed to seaman.

Languid.description: Drooping or flagging from exhaustion; indisposed to exertion; without animation; weak; weary; heavy; dull.

Lank.description: Slender and thin; not well filled out; not plump; shrunken; lean.

Lanolin.description: A peculiar fatlike body, made up of cholesterin and certain fatty acids, found in feathers, hair, wool, and keratin tissues generally.

Lapdog.description: A small dog fondled in the lap.

Lapel.description: That part of a garment which is turned back; specifically, the lap, or fold, of the front of a coat in continuation of collar.

Lapidary.description: An artificer who cuts, polishes, and engraves precious stones; hence, a dealer in precious stones.

Larceny.description: The unlawful taking and carrying away of things personal with intent to deprive the right owner of the same; theft.  Cf. Embezzlement.

Largo.description: Slow or slowly; -- more so than adagio; next in slowness to grave, which is also weighty and solemn.

Lariat.description: A long, slender rope made of hemp or strips of hide, esp. one with a noose; -- used as a lasso for catching cattle, horses, etc., and for picketing a horse so that he can graze without wandering.

Larine.description: Of or pertaining to the Gull family (Laridae).

Larva.description: Any young insect from the time that it hatches from the egg until it becomes a pupa, or chrysalis. During this time it usually molts several times, and may change its form or color each time. The larvae of many insects are much like the adults in form and habits, but have no trace of wings, the rudimentary wings appearing only in the pupa stage. In other groups of insects the larvae are totally unlike the parents in structure and habits, and are called caterpillars, grubs, maggots, etc.

Larval.description: Of or pertaining to a larva.

Last.description: of Last, to endure, contracted from lasteth.

Lastly.description: In the last place; in conclusion.

Latency.description: The state or quality of being latent.

Latent.description: Not visible or apparent; hidden; springs of action.

Latin.description: Of or pertaining to Latium, or to the Latins, a people of Latium; Roman; as, the Latin language.

Latitudinal.description: Of or pertaining to latitude; in the direction of latitude.

Lava.description: The melted rock ejected by a volcano from its top or fissured sides. It flows out in streams sometimes miles in length. It also issues from fissures in the earth's surface, and forms beds covering many square miles, as in the Northwestern United States.

Laxative.description: Having a tendency to loosen or relax.

Lazuli.description: A mineral of a fine azure-blue color, usually in small rounded masses. It is essentially a silicate of alumina, lime, and soda, with some sodium sulphide, is often marked by yellow spots or veins of sulphide of iron, and is much valued for ornamental work. Called also lapis lazuli, and Armenian stone.

Lazy.description: Disinclined to action or exertion; averse to labor; idle; shirking work.

Legacy.description: A gift of property by will, esp. of money or personal property; a bequest. Also Fig.; as, a legacy of dishonor or disease.

Legal.description: Created by, permitted by, in conformity with, or relating to, law; as, a legal obligation; a legal standard or test; a legal procedure; a legal claim; a legal trade; anything is legal which the laws do not forbid.

Legality.description: The state or quality of being legal; conformity to law.

Legato.description: Connected; tied; -- a term used when successive tones are to be produced in a closely connected, smoothly gliding manner. It is often indicated by a tie, thus /, /, or /, /, written over or under the notes to be so performed; -- opposed to staccato.

Legend.description: That which is appointed to be read; especially, a chronicle or register of the lives of saints, formerly read at matins, and in the refectories of religious houses.

Legendary.description: Of or pertaining to a legend or to legends; consisting of legends; like a legend; fabulous.

Leghorn.description: A straw plaiting used for bonnets and hats, made from the straw of a particular kind of wheat, grown for the purpose in Tuscany, Italy; -- so called from Leghorn, the place of exportation.

Legibility.description: The quality of being legible; legibleness.

Legible.description: Capable of being read or deciphered; distinct to the eye; plain; -- used of writing or printing; as, a fair, legible manuscript.

Legitimacy.description: The state, or quality, of being legitimate, or in conformity with law; hence, the condition of having been lawfully begotten, or born in wedlock.

Legume.description: A pod dehiscent into two pieces or valves, and having the seed attached at one suture, as that of the pea.

Leman.description: A sweetheart, of either sex; a gallant, or a mistress; -- usually in a bad sense.

Lemon.description: An oval or roundish fruit resembling the orange, and containing a pulp usually intensely acid. It is produced by a tropical tree of the genus Citrus, the common fruit known in commerce being that of the species C. Limonum or C. Medica (var. Limonum). There are many varieties of the fruit, some of which are sweet.

Lend.description: To allow the custody and use of, on condition of the return of the same; to grant the temporary use of; as, to lend a book; -- opposed to borrow.

Leniency.description: The quality or state of being lenient; lenity; clemency.

Lenient.description: Relaxing; emollient; softening; assuasive; -- sometimes followed by of.

Leno.description: A light open cotton fabric used for window curtains.

Lens.description: A piece of glass, or other transparent substance, ground with two opposite regular surfaces, either both curved, or one curved and the other plane, and commonly used, either singly or combined, in optical instruments, for changing the direction of rays of light, and thus magnifying objects, or otherwise modifying vision. In practice, the curved surfaces are usually spherical, though rarely cylindrical, or of some other figure.

Lentil.description: A leguminous plant of the genus Ervum (Ervum Lens), of small size, common in the fields in Europe. Also, its seed, which is used for food on the continent.

Lento.description: Slow; in slow time; slowly; -- rarely written lente.

Leonid.description: One of the shooting stars which constitute the star shower that recurs near the fourteenth of November at intervals of about thirty-three years; -- so called because these shooting stars appear on the heavens to move in lines directed from the constellation Leo.

Leprosy.description: A cutaneous disease which first appears as blebs or as reddish, shining, slightly prominent spots, with spreading edges. These are often followed by an eruption of dark or yellowish prominent nodules, frequently producing great deformity. In one variety of the disease, anaesthesia of the skin is a prominent symptom. In addition there may be wasting of the muscles, falling out of the hair and nails, and distortion of the hands and feet with destruction of the bones and joints. It is incurable, and is probably contagious.

Lesbian.description: Of or pertaining to the island anciently called Lesbos, now Mitylene, in the Grecian Archipelago.

Levana.description: A goddess who protected newborn infants.

Levant.description: Rising or having risen from rest; -- said of cattle. See Couchant and levant, under Couchant.

Level.description: A line or surface to which, at every point, a vertical or plumb line is perpendicular; a line or surface which is everywhere parallel to the surface of still water; -- this is the true level, and is a curve or surface in which all points are equally distant from the center of the earth, or rather would be so if the earth were an exact sphere.

Leviticus.description: The third canonical book of the Old Testament, containing the laws and regulations relating to the priests and Levites among the Hebrews, or the body of the ceremonial law.

Levity.description: The quality of weighing less than something else of equal bulk; relative lightness, especially as shown by rising through, or floating upon, a contiguous substance; buoyancy; -- opposed to gravity.

Levy.description: A name formerly given in Pennsylvania, Maryland, and Virginia to the Spanish real of one eighth of a dollar (or 12/ cents), valued at eleven pence when the dollar was rated at 7s. 6d.

Liability.description: The state of being liable; as, the liability of an insurer; liability to accidents; liability to the law.

Liable.description: Bound or obliged in law or equity; responsible; answerable; as, the surety is liable for the debt of his principal.

Liana.description: A luxuriant woody plant, climbing high trees and having ropelike stems. The grapevine often has the habit of a liane. Lianes are abundant in the forests of the Amazon region.

Libel.description: A brief writing of any kind, esp. a declaration, bill, certificate, request, supplication, etc.

Liberalism.description: Liberal principles; the principles and methods of the liberals in politics or religion; specifically, the principles of the Liberal party.

Libra.description: The Balance; the seventh sign in the zodiac, which the sun enters at the autumnal equinox in September, marked thus / in almanacs, etc.

Librarian.description: One who has the care or charge of a library.

Library.description: A considerable collection of books kept for use, and not as merchandise; as, a private library; a public library.

Libyan.description: Of or pertaining to Libya, the ancient name of that part of Africa between Egypt and the Atlantic Ocean, or of Africa as a whole.

Lift.description: The sky; the atmosphere; the firmament.

Ligament.description: Anything that ties or unites one thing or part to another; a bandage; a bond.

Lignin.description: A substance characterizing wood cells and differing from cellulose in its conduct with certain chemical reagents.

Madam.description: A gentlewoman; -- an appellation or courteous form of address given to a lady, especially an elderly or a married lady; -- much used in the address, at the beginning of a letter, to a woman. The corresponding word in addressing a man is Sir.

Madcap.description: Inclined to wild sports; delighting in rash, absurd, or dangerous amusements.

Madia.description: A genus of composite plants, of which one species (Madia sativa) is cultivated for the oil yielded from its seeds by pressure. This oil is sometimes used instead of olive oil for the table.

Madly.description: In a mad manner; without reason or understanding; wildly.

Madman.description: A man who is mad; lunatic; a crazy person.

Madrigal.description: A little amorous poem, sometimes called a pastoral poem, containing some tender and delicate, though simple, thought.

Nabob.description: A deputy or viceroy in India; a governor of a province of the ancient Mogul empire.

Naivete.description: Native simplicity; unaffected plainness or ingenuousness; artlessness.

Naked.description: Having no clothes on; uncovered; nude; bare; as, a naked body; a naked limb; a naked sword.

Napkin.description: A little towel, or small cloth, esp. one for wiping the fingers and mouth at table.

Napoleon.description: A French gold coin of twenty francs, or about $3.86.

Napoleonic.description: Of or pertaining to Napoleon I., or his family; resembling, or having the qualities of, Napoleon I.

Narcotic.description: Having the properties of a narcotic; operating as a narcotic.

Nard.description: An East Indian plant (Nardostachys Jatamansi) of the Valerian family, used from remote ages in Oriental perfumery.

Nasal.description: Of or pertaining to the nose.

Nasty.description: Offensively filthy; very dirty, foul, or defiled; disgusting; nauseous.

Natal.description: Of or pertaining to one's birth; accompying or dating from one's birth; native.

Nationalism.description: The state of being national; national attachment; nationality.

Nativity.description: The coming into life or into the world; birth; also, the circumstances attending birth, as time, place, manner, etc.

Naturalism.description: A state of nature; conformity to nature.

Naval.description: Having to do with shipping; of or pertaining to ships or a navy; consisting of ships; as, naval forces, successes, stores, etc.

Navel.description: A mark or depression in the middle of the abdomen; the umbilicus. See Umbilicus.

Navigable.description: Capable of being navigated; deep enough and wide enough to afford passage to vessels; as, a navigable river.

Navy.description: A fleet of ships; an assemblage of merchantmen, or so many as sail in company.

Neapolitan.description: Of of pertaining to Naples in Italy.

Necrologist.description: One who gives an account of deaths.

Necrology.description: An account of deaths, or of the dead; a register of deaths; a collection of obituary notices.

Necromancy.description: The art of revealing future events by means of a pretended communication with the dead; the black art; hence, magic in general; conjuration; enchantment. See Black art.

Necropolis.description: A city of the dead; a name given by the ancients to their cemeteries, and sometimes applied to modern burial places; a graveyard.

Necrosis.description: Mortification or gangrene of bone, or the death of a bone or portion of a bone in mass, as opposed to its death by molecular disintegration. See Caries.

Negativity.description: The quality or state of being negative.

Neglect.description: Not to attend to with due care or attention; to forbear one's duty in regard to; to suffer to pass unimproved, unheeded, undone, etc.; to omit; to disregard; to slight; as, to neglect duty or business; to neglect to pay debts.

Neglectful.description: Full of neglect; heedless; careless; negligent; inattentive; indifferent.

Negligent.description: Apt to neglect; customarily neglectful; characterized by negligence; careless; heedless; culpably careless; showing lack of attention; as, disposed in negligent order.

Negligible.description: That may neglicted, disregarded, or left out of consideration.

Negro.description: A black man; especially, one of a race of black or very dark persons who inhabit the greater part of tropical Africa, and are distinguished by crisped or curly hair, flat noses, and thick protruding lips; also, any black person of unmixed African blood, wherever found.

Negus.description: A beverage made of wine, water, sugar, nutmeg, and lemon juice; -- so called, it is said, from its first maker, Colonel Negus.

Nemean.description: Of or pertaining to Nemea, in Argolis, where the ancient Greeks celebrated games, and Hercules killed a lion.

Nemesis.description: The goddess of retribution or vengeance; hence, retributive justice personified; divine vengeance.

Neoplatonic.description: Of, pertaining to, or resembling, Neoplatonism or the Neoplatonists.

Neoplatonist.description: One who held to Neoplatonism; a member of the Neoplatonic school.

Nepa.description: A genus of aquatic hemipterus insects. The species feed upon other insects and are noted for their voracity; -- called also scorpion bug and water scorpion.

Neptunium.description: A new metallic element, of doubtful genuineness and uncertain indentification, said to exist in certain minerals, as columbite.

Nero.description: A Roman emperor notorius for debauchery and barbarous cruelty; hence, any profligate and cruel ruler or merciless tyrant.

Nest.description: The bed or receptacle prepared by a fowl for holding her eggs and for hatching and rearing her young.

Nestorian.description: An adherent of Nestorius, patriarch of Constantinople to the fifth century, who has condemned as a heretic for maintaining that the divine and the human natures were not merged into one nature in Christ (who was God in man), and, hence, that it was improper to call Mary the mother of Christ; also, one of the sect established by the followers of Nestorius in Persia, india, and other Oriental countries, and still in existence. opposed to Eutychian.

Nicety.description: The quality or state of being nice (in any of the senses of that word.).

Nimble.description: Light and quick in motion; moving with ease and celerity; lively; swift.

Nimbly.description: In a nimble manner; with agility; with light, quick motion.

Nimbus.description: A circle, or disk, or any indication of radiant light around the heads of divinities, saints, and sovereigns, upon medals, pictures, etc.; a halo. See Aureola, and Glory, n., 5.

Niobium.description: A later name of columbium. See Columbium.

Nirvana.description: In the Buddhist system of religion, the final emancipation of the soul from transmigration, and consequently a beatific enfrachisement from the evils of wordly existence, as by annihilation or absorption into the divine. See Buddhism.

Nitric.description: Of, pertaining to, or containing, nitrogen; specifically, designating any one of those compounds in which, as contrasted with nitrous compounds, the element has a higher valence; as, nitric oxide; nitric acid.

Nitrogen.description: A colorless nonmetallic element, tasteless and odorless, comprising four fifths of the atmosphere by volume. It is chemically very inert in the free state, and as such is incapable of supporting life (hence the name azote still used by French chemists); but it forms many important compounds, as ammonia, nitric acid, the cyanides, etc, and is a constituent of all organized living tissues, animal or vegetable. Symbol N. Atomic weight 14. It was formerly regarded as a permanent noncondensible gas, but was liquefied in 1877 by Cailletet of Paris, and Pictet of Geneva.

Nobility.description: The quality or state of being noble; superiority of mind or of character; commanding excellence; eminence.

Noble.description: Possessing eminence, elevation, dignity, etc.; above whatever is low, mean, degrading, or dishonorable; magnanimous; as, a noble nature or action; a noble heart.

Nobleman.description: One of the nobility; a noble; a peer; one who enjoys rank above a commoner, either by virtue of birth, by office, or by patent.

Noblewoman.description: A female of noble rank; a peeress.

Nobly.description: Of noble extraction; as, nobly born or descended.

Nobody.description: No person; no one; not anybody.

Nomad.description: One of a race or tribe that has no fixed location, but wanders from place to place in search of pasture or game.

Nomadic.description: Of or pertaining to nomads, or their way of life; wandering; moving from place to place for subsistence; as, a nomadic tribe.

Nominal.description: Of or pertaining to a name or names; having to do with the literal meaning of a word; verbal; as, a nominal definition.

Noncombatant.description: Any person connected with an army, or within the lines of an army, who does not make it his business to fight, as any one of the medical officers and their assistants, chaplains, and others; also, any of the citizens of a place occupied by an army; also, any one holding a similar position with respect to the navy.

Nonconformist.description: One who does not conform to an established church; especially, one who does not conform to the established church of England; a dissenter.

Nonconformity.description: Neglect or failure of conformity; especially, in England, the neglect or refusal to unite with the established church in its rites and modes of worship.

Nondescript.description: Not hitherto described; novel; hence, odd; abnormal; unclassifiable.

Nonresident.description: Not residing in a particular place, on one's own estate, or in one's proper place; as, a nonresident clergyman or proprietor of lands.

Nonsensical.description: Without sense; unmeaning; absurb; foolish; irrational; preposterous.

Norm.description: A rule or authoritative standard; a model; a type.

Norma.description: A norm; a principle or rule; a model; a standard.

Normal.description: According to an established norm, rule, or principle; conformed to a type, standard, or regular form; performing the proper functions; not abnormal; regular; natural; analogical.

Normalcy.description: The quality, state, or fact of being normal; as, the point of normalcy.

Norman.description: A wooden bar, or iron pin.

Norna.description: One of the three Fates, Past, Present, and Future. Their names were Urd, Verdandi, and Skuld.

Nostalgic.description: Of or pertaining to nostalgia; affected with nostalgia.

Nostril.description: One of the external openings of the nose, which give passage to the air breathed and to secretions from the nose and eyes; one of the anterior nares.

Notable.description: Capable of being noted; noticeable; plan; evident.

Notify.description: To make known; to declare; to publish; as, to notify a fact to a person.

Novel.description: Of recent origin or introduction; not ancient; new; hence, out of the ordinary course; unusual; strange; surprising.

Novelist.description: An innovator; an asserter of novelty.

Novelty.description: The quality or state of being novel; newness; freshness; recentness of origin or introduction.

Novum.description: A game at dice, properly called novem quinque (L., nine five), the two principal throws being nine and five.

Nucleus.description: A kernel; hence, a central mass or point about which matter is gathered, or to which accretion is made; the central or material portion; -- used both literally and figuratively.

Nudity.description: The quality or state of being nude; nakedness.

Numerical.description: Belonging to number; denoting number; consisting in numbers; expressed by numbers, and not letters; as, numerical characters; a numerical equation; a numerical statement.

Oasis.description: A fertile or green spot in a waste or desert, esp. in a sandy desert.

Obedient.description: Subject in will or act to authority; willing to obey; submissive to restraint, control, or command.

Obediently.description: In an obedient manner; with obedience.

Paca.description: A small South American rodent (Coelogenys paca), having blackish brown fur, with four parallel rows of white spots along its sides; the spotted cavy. It is nearly allied to the agouti and the Guinea pig.

Pacific.description: Of or pertaining to peace; suited to make or restore peace; of a peaceful character; not warlike; not quarrelsome; conciliatory; as, pacific words or acts; a pacific nature or condition.

Pacify.description: To make to be at peace; to appease; to calm; to still; to quiet; to allay the agitation, excitement, or resentment of; to tranquillize; as, to pacify a man when angry; to pacify pride, appetite, or importunity.

Pact.description: An agreement; a league; a compact; a covenant.

Pagan.description: One who worships false gods; an idolater; a heathen; one who is neither a Christian, a Mohammedan, nor a Jew.

Pagoda.description: A term by which Europeans designate religious temples and tower-like buildings of the Hindoos and Buddhists of India, Farther India, China, and Japan, -- usually but not always, devoted to idol worship.

Paladin.description: A knight-errant; a distinguished champion; as, the paladins of Charlemagne.

Palatable.description: Agreeable to the palate or taste; savory; hence, acceptable; pleasing; as, palatable food; palatable advice.

Paleobotany.description: That branch of paleontology which treats of fossil plants.

Paleontology.description: The science which treats of the ancient life of the earth, or of fossils which are the remains of such life.

Paleozoic.description: Of or pertaining to, or designating, the older division of geological time during which life is known to have existed, including the Silurian, Devonian, and Carboniferous ages, and also to the life or rocks of those ages. See Chart of Geology.

Quadra.description: The plinth, or lowest member, of any pedestal, podium, water table, or the like.

Racy.description: Having a strong flavor indicating origin; of distinct characteristic taste; tasting of the soil; hence, fresh; rich.

Radial.description: Of or pertaining to a radius or ray; consisting of, or like, radii or rays; radiated; as, (Bot.) radial projections; (Zool.) radial vessels or canals; (Anat.) the radial artery.

Radiant.description: Emitting or proceeding as from a center; resembling rays; radiating; radiate.

Radical.description: Of or pertaining to the root; proceeding directly from the root.

Radius.description: A right line drawn or extending from the center of a circle to the periphery; the semidiameter of a circle or sphere.

Raia.description: A genus of rays which includes the skates. See Skate.

Ramble.description: To walk, ride, or sail, from place to place, without any determinate object in view; to roam carelessly or irregularly; to rove; to wander; as, to ramble about the city; to ramble over the world.

Ramify.description: To divide into branches or subdivisions; as, to ramify an art, subject, scheme.

Ramp.description: To spring; to leap; to bound; to rear; to prance; to become rampant; hence, to frolic; to romp.

Rampant.description: Ramping; leaping; springing; rearing upon the hind legs; hence, raging; furious.

Ramrod.description: The rod used in ramming home the charge in a muzzle-loading firearm.

Ramus.description: A branch; a projecting part or prominent process; a ramification.

Rana.description: A genus of anurous batrachians, including the common frogs.

Rancid.description: Having a rank smell or taste, from chemical change or decomposition; musty; as, rancid oil or butter.

Rancidity.description: The quality or state of being rancid; a rancid scent or flavor, as of old oil.

Rani.description: A queen or princess; the wife of a rajah.

Rank.description: Luxuriant in growth; of vigorous growth; exuberant; grown to immoderate height; as, rank grass; rank weeds.

Rankle.description: To become, or be, rank; to grow rank or strong; to be inflamed; to fester; -- used literally and figuratively.

Ransom.description: The release of a captive, or of captured property, by payment of a consideration; redemption; as, prisoners hopeless of ransom.

Rant.description: To rave in violent, high-sounding, or extravagant language, without dignity of thought; to be noisy, boisterous, and bombastic in talk or declamation; as, a ranting preacher.

Rapid.description: Very swift or quick; moving with celerity; fast; as, a rapid stream; a rapid flight; a rapid motion.

Rapidity.description: The quality or state of being rapid; swiftness; celerity; velocity; as, the rapidity of a current; rapidity of speech; rapidity of growth or improvement.

Raptorial.description: Rapacious; living upon prey; -- said especially of certain birds.

Rarefy.description: To make rare, thin, porous, or less dense; to expand or enlarge without adding any new portion of matter to; -- opposed to condense.

Rarity.description: The quality or state of being rare; rareness; thinness; as, the rarity (contrasted with the density) of gases.

Rascal.description: One of the rabble; a low, common sort of person or creature; collectively, the rabble; the common herd; also, a lean, ill-conditioned beast, esp. a deer.

Rasp.description: To rub or file with a rasp; to rub or grate with a rough file; as, to rasp wood to make it smooth; to rasp bones to powder.

Raspy.description: Like a rasp, or the sound made by a rasp; grating.

Rata.description: A New Zealand forest tree (Metrosideros robusta), also, its hard dark red wood, used by the Maoris for paddles and war clubs.

Ratify.description: To approve and sanction; to make valid; to confirm; to establish; to settle; especially, to give sanction to, as something done by an agent or servant; as, to ratify an agreement, treaty, or contract; to ratify a nomination.

Ratio.description: The relation which one quantity or magnitude has to another of the same kind. It is expressed by the quotient of the division of the first by the second; thus, the ratio of 3 to 6 is expressed by / or /; of a to b by a/b; or (less commonly) the second term is made the dividend; as, a:b = b/a.

Ravel.description: To separate or undo the texture of; to take apart; to untwist; to unweave or unknit; -- often followed by out; as, to ravel a twist; to ravel out a stocking.

Raven.description: A large black passerine bird (Corvus corax), similar to the crow, but larger. It is native of the northern parts of Europe, Asia, and America, and is noted for its sagacity.

Reabsorb.description: To absorb again; to draw in, or imbibe, again what has been effused, extravasated, or thrown off; to swallow up again; as, to reabsorb chyle, lymph, etc.; -- used esp. of fluids.

React.description: To act or perform a second time; to do over again; as, to react a play; the same scenes were reacted at Rome.

Readmit.description: To admit again; to give entrance or access to again.

Reagent.description: A substance capable of producing with another a reaction, especially when employed to detect the presence of other bodies; a test.

Realism.description: As opposed to nominalism, the doctrine that genera and species are real things or entities, existing independently of our conceptions. According to realism the Universal exists ante rem (Plato), or in re (Aristotle).

Realistic.description: Of or pertaining to the realists; in the manner of the realists; characterized by realism rather than by imagination.

Reality.description: The state or quality of being real; actual being or existence of anything, in distinction from mere appearance; fact.

Rebel.description: Pertaining to rebels or rebellion; acting in revolt; rebellious; as, rebel troops.

Rebuke.description: To check, silence, or put down, with reproof; to restrain by expression of disapprobation; to reprehend sharply and summarily; to chide; to reprove; to admonish.

Rebus.description: A mode of expressing words and phrases by pictures of objects whose names resemble those words, or the syllables of which they are composed; enigmatical representation of words by figures; hence, a peculiar form of riddle made up of such representations.

Rebut.description: To drive or beat back; to repulse.

Recalcitrant.description: Kicking back; recalcitrating; hence, showing repugnance or opposition; refractory.

Recant.description: To withdraw or repudiate formally and publicly (opinions formerly expressed); to contradict, as a former declaration; to take back openly; to retract; to recall.

Recent.description: Of late origin, existence, or occurrence; lately come; not of remote date, antiquated style, or the like; not already known, familiar, worn out, trite, etc.; fresh; novel; new; modern; as, recent news.

Recently.description: Newly; lately; freshly; not long since; as, advices recently received.

Receptacle.description: That which serves, or is used, for receiving and containing something, as a basket, a vase, a bag, a reservoir; a repository.

Receptivity.description: The state or quality of being receptive.

Recipe.description: A formulary or prescription for making some combination, mixture, or preparation of materials; a receipt; especially, a prescription for medicine.

Recipient.description: A receiver; the person or thing that receives; one to whom, or that to which, anything is given or communicated; specifically, the receiver of a still.

Recital.description: The act of reciting; the repetition of the words of another, or of a document; rehearsal; as, the recital of testimony.

Reconstruct.description: To construct again; to rebuild; to remodel; to form again or anew.

Record.description: To recall to mind; to recollect; to remember; to meditate.

Rectal.description: Of or pertaining to the rectum; in the region of the rectum.

Rectangle.description: A four-sided figure having only right angles; a right-angled parallelogram.

Rectangular.description: Right-angled; having one or more angles of ninety degrees.

Rectify.description: To make or set right; to correct from a wrong, erroneous, or false state; to amend; as, to rectify errors, mistakes, or abuses; to rectify the will, the judgment, opinions; to rectify disorders.

Rectum.description: The terminal part of the large intestine; -- so named because supposed by the old anatomists to be straight. See Illust. under Digestive.

Recuse.description: To refuse or reject, as a judge; to challenge that the judge shall not try the cause.

Redact.description: To reduce to form, as literary matter; to digest and put in shape (matter for publication); to edit.

Redbud.description: A small ornamental leguminous tree of the American species of the genus Cercis. See Judas tree, under Judas.

Redolent.description: Diffusing odor or fragrance; spreading sweet scent; scented; odorous; smelling; -- usually followed by of.

Redskin.description: A common appellation for a North American Indian; -- so called from the color of the skin.

Redundancy.description: The quality or state of being redundant; superfluity; superabundance; excess.

Redundant.description: Exceeding what is natural or necessary; superabundant; exuberant; as, a redundant quantity of bile or food.

Reelect.description: To elect again; as, to reelect the former governor.

Reenactment.description: The enacting or passing of a law a second time; the renewal of a law.

Reentry.description: A second or new entry; as, a reentry into public life.

Reexamination.description: A repeated examination. See under Examination.

Refit.description: To fit or prepare for use again; to repair; to restore after damage or decay; as, to refit a garment; to refit ships of war.

Reflect.description: To bend back; to give a backwa/d turn to; to throw back; especially, to cause to return after striking upon any surface; as, a mirror reflects rays of light; polished metals reflect heat.

Reflexive.description: Bending or turned backward; reflective; having respect to something past.

Reform.description: To put into a new and improved form or condition; to restore to a former good state, or bring from bad to good; to change from worse to better; to amend; to correct; as, to reform a profligate man; to reform corrupt manners or morals.

Refuge.description: Shelter or protection from danger or distress.

Refugee.description: One who flees to a shelter, or place of safety.

Refund.description: To fund again or anew; to replace (a fund or loan) by a new fund; as, to refund a railroad loan.

Refuse.description: To deny, as a request, demand, invitation, or command; to decline to do or grant.

Refutation.description: The act or process of refuting or disproving, or the state of being refuted; proof of falsehood or error; the overthrowing of an argument, opinion, testimony, doctrine, or theory, by argument or countervailing proof.

Refute.description: To disprove and overthrow by argument, evidence, or countervailing proof; to prove to be false or erroneous; to confute; as, to refute arguments; to refute testimony; to refute opinions or theories; to refute a disputant.

Regal.description: Of or pertaining to a king; kingly; royal; as, regal authority, pomp, or sway.

Regalia.description: That which belongs to royalty. Specifically: (a) The rights and prerogatives of a king. (b) Royal estates and revenues. (c) Ensings, symbols, or paraphernalia of royalty.

Regard.description: To keep in view; to behold; to look at; to view; to gaze upon.

Regency.description: The office of ruler; rule; authority; government.

Regimen.description: Orderly government; system of order; adminisration.

Regiment.description: Government; mode of ruling; rule; authority; regimen.

Regimental.description: Belonging to, or concerning, a regiment; as, regimental officers, clothing.

Registrant.description: One who registers; esp., one who , by virtue of securing an official registration, obtains a certain right or title of possession, as to a trade-mark.

Registrar.description: One who registers; a recorder; a keeper of records; as, a registrar of births, deaths, and marriages. See Register, n., 3.

Registry.description: The act of recording or writing in a register; enrollment; registration.

Regret.description: Pain of mind on account of something done or experienced in the past, with a wish that it had been different; a looking back with dissatisfaction or with longing; grief; sorrow; especially, a mourning on account of the loss of some joy, advantage, or satisfaction.

Regretful.description: Full of regret; indulging in regrets; repining.

Regular.description: Conformed to a rule; agreeable to an established rule, law, principle, or type, or to established customary forms; normal; symmetrical; as, a regular verse in poetry; a regular piece of music; a regular verb; regular practice of law or medicine; a regular building.

Regularly.description: In a regular manner; in uniform order; methodically; in due order or time.

Regulate.description: To adjust by rule, method, or established mode; to direct by rule or restriction; to subject to governing principles or laws.

Regulation.description: The act of regulating, or the state of being regulated.

Regulator.description: One who, or that which, regulates.

Reinvestment.description: The act of investing anew; a second or repeated investment.

Reject.description: To cast from one; to throw away; to discard.

Relativity.description: The state of being relative; as, the relativity of a subject.

Relaxation.description: The act or process of relaxing, or the state of being relaxed; as, relaxation of the muscles; relaxation of a law.

Relent.description: To become less rigid or hard; to yield; to dissolve; to melt; to deliquesce.

Relevancy.description: The quality or state of being relevant; pertinency; applicability.

Reliability.description: The state or quality of being reliable; reliableness.

Reliable.description: Suitable or fit to be relied on; worthy of dependance or reliance; trustworthy.

Reliant.description: Having, or characterized by, reliance; confident; trusting.

Relic.description: That which remains; that which is left after loss or decay; a remaining portion; a remnant.

Religiosity.description: The quality of being religious; religious feeling or sentiment; religiousness.

Reluctant.description: Striving against; opposed in desire; unwilling; disinclined; loth.

Rely.description: To rest with confidence, as when fully satisfied of the veracity, integrity, or ability of persons, or of the certainty of facts or of evidence; to have confidence; to trust; to depend; -- with on, formerly also with in.

Remark.description: To mark in a notable manner; to distinquish clearly; to make noticeable or conspicuous; to piont out.

Remarkable.description: Worthy of being remarked or noticed; noticeable; conspicuous; hence, uncommon; extraordinary.

Remedial.description: Affording a remedy; intended for a remedy, or for the removal or abatement of an evil; as, remedial treatment.

Remedy.description: That which relieves or cures a disease; any medicine or application which puts an end to disease and restores health; -- with for; as, a remedy for the gout.

Remind.description: To put (one) in mind of something; to bring to the remembrance of; to bring to the notice or consideration of (a person).

Remit.description: To send back; to give up; to surrender; to resign.

Remodel.description: To model or fashion anew; to change the form of.

Removal.description: The act of removing, or the state of being removed.

Renal.description: Of or pertaining to the kidneys; in the region of the kidneys.

Renard.description: A fox; -- so called in fables or familiar tales, and in poetry.

Rentable.description: Capable of being rented, or suitable for renting.

Rental.description: A schedule, account, or list of rents, with the names of the tenants, etc.; a rent roll.

Repel.description: To drive back; to force to return; to check the advance of; to repulse as, to repel an enemy or an assailant.

Repent.description: Prostrate and rooting; -- said of stems.

Replica.description: A copy of a work of art, as of a picture or statue, made by the maker of the original.

Replicated.description: Folded over or backward; folded back upon itself; as, a replicate leaf or petal; a replicate margin of a shell.

Reply.description: To make a return in words or writing; to respond; to answer.

Reportable.description: Capable or admitting of being reported.

Repository.description: A place where things are or may be reposited, or laid up, for safety or preservation; a depository.

Reprehensible.description: Worthy of reprehension; culpable; censurable; blamable.

Represent.description: To present again or anew; to present by means of something standing in the place of; to exhibit the counterpart or image of; to typify.

Reprimand.description: Severe or formal reproof; reprehension, private or public.

Reprint.description: To print again; to print a second or a new edition of.

Reprisal.description: The act of taking from an enemy by way of reteliation or indemnity.

Republican.description: Of or pertaining to a republic.

Repudiate.description: To cast off; to disavow; to have nothing to do with; to renounce; to reject.

Repudiation.description: The act of repudiating, or the state of being repuddiated; as, the repudiation of a doctrine, a wife, a debt, etc.

Repugnant.description: Disposed to fight against; hostile; at war with; being at variance; contrary; inconsistent; refractory; disobedient; also, distasteful in a high degree; offensive; -- usually followed by to, rarely and less properly by with; as, all rudeness was repugnant to her nature.

Reputation.description: The estimation in which one is held; character in public opinion; the character attributed to a person, thing, or action; repute.

Repute.description: To hold in thought; to account; to estimate; to hold; to think; to reckon.

Request.description: The act of asking for anything desired; expression of desire or demand; solicitation; prayer; petition; entreaty.

Requiem.description: A mass said or sung for the repose of a departed soul.

Rescue.description: To free or deliver from any confinement, violence, danger, or evil; to liberate from actual restraint; to remove or withdraw from a state of exposure to evil; as, to rescue a prisoner from the enemy; to rescue seamen from destruction.

Reseda.description: A genus of plants, the type of which is mignonette.

Resemble.description: To be like or similar to; to bear the similitude of, either in appearance or qualities; as, these brothers resemble each other.

Resent.description: To be sensible of; to feel

Resentful.description: Inclined to resent; easily provoked to anger; irritable.

Reset.description: To set again; as, to reset type; to reset copy; to reset a diamond.

Resident.description: Dwelling, or having an abode, in a place for a continued length of time; residing on one's own estate; -- opposed to nonresident; as, resident in the city or in the country.

Residual.description: Pertaining to a residue; remaining after a part is taken.

Resiliency.description: The act of resiling, springing back, or rebounding; as, the resilience of a ball or of sound.

Resin.description: Any one of a class of yellowish brown solid inflammable substances, of vegetable origin, which are nonconductors of electricity, have a vitreous fracture, and are soluble in ether, alcohol, and essential oils, but not in water; specif., pine resin (see Rosin).

Resist.description: To stand against; to withstand; to obstruct.

Resonant.description: Returning, or capable of returning, sound; fitted to resound; resounding; echoing back.

Respect.description: To take notice of; to regard with special attention; to regard as worthy of special consideration; hence, to care for; to heed.

Respectability.description: The state or quality of being respectable; the state or quality which deserves or commands respect.

Respectable.description: Worthy of respect; fitted to awaken esteem; deserving regard; hence, of good repute; not mean; as, a respectable citizen.

Respectful.description: Marked or characterized by respect; as, respectful deportment.

Resplendent.description: Shining with brilliant luster; very bright.

Respond.description: To say somethin in return; to answer; to reply; as, to respond to a question or an argument.

Respondent.description: Disposed or expected to respond; answering; according; corresponding.

Responsibility.description: The state of being responsible, accountable, or answerable, as for a trust, debt, or obligation.

Responsible.description: Liable to respond; likely to be called upon to answer; accountable; answerable; amenable; as, a guardian is responsible to the court for his conduct in the office.

Resultant.description: Resulting or issuing from a combination; existing or following as a result or consequence.

Retaliatory.description: Tending to, or involving, retaliation; retaliative; as retaliatory measures.

Retard.description: To keep delaying; to continue to hinder; to prevent from progress; to render more slow in progress; to impede; to hinder; as, to retard the march of an army; to retard the motion of a ship; -- opposed to accelerate.

Reticent.description: Inclined to keep silent; reserved; uncommunicative.

Retina.description: The delicate membrane by which the back part of the globe of the eye is lined, and in which the fibers of the optic nerve terminate. See Eye.

Retinal.description: Of or pertaining to the retina.

Retort.description: To bend or curve back; as, a retorted line.

Retract.description: To draw back; to draw up or shorten; as, the cat can retract its claws; to retract a muscle.

Retrial.description: A secdond trial, experiment, or test; a second judicial trial, as of an accused person.

Retrospect.description: To look backward; hence, to affect or concern what is past.

Retry.description: To try (esp. judicially) a second time; as, to retry a case; to retry an accused person.

Reunion.description: A second union; union formed anew after separation, secession, or discord; as, a reunion of parts or particles of matter; a reunion of parties or sects.

Revamp.description: To vamp again; hence, to patch up; to reconstruct.

Revelry.description: The act of engaging in a revel; noisy festivity; reveling.

Revival.description: The act of reviving, or the state of being revived.

Revivalist.description: A clergyman or layman who promotes revivals of religion; an advocate for religious revivals; sometimes, specifically, a clergyman, without a particular charge, who goes about to promote revivals. Also used adjectively.

Revocable.description: Capable of being revoked; as, a revocable edict or grant; a revocable covenant.

Revolt.description: To turn away; to abandon or reject something; specifically, to turn away, or shrink, with abhorrence.

Reward.description: To give in return, whether good or evil; -- commonly in a good sense; to requite; to recompense; to repay; to compensate.

Ribald.description: A low, vulgar, brutal, foul-mouthed wretch; a lewd fellow.

Ribaldry.description: The talk of a ribald; low, vulgar language; indecency; obscenity; lewdness; -- now chiefly applied to indecent language, but formerly, as by Chaucer, also to indecent acts or conduct.

Ridable.description: Suitable for riding; as, a ridable horse; a ridable road.

Riden.description: imp. pl. & p. p. of Ride.

Ridicule.description: An object of sport or laughter; a laughingstock; a laughing matter.

Ridiculous.description: Fitted to excite ridicule; absurd and laughable; unworthy of serious consideration; as, a ridiculous dress or behavior.

Rifle.description: To seize and bear away by force; to snatch away; to carry off.

Rigel.description: A fixed star of the first magnitude in the left foot of the constellation Orion.

Rigid.description: Firm; stiff; unyielding; not pliant; not flexible.

Rigidity.description: The quality or state of being rigid; want of pliability; the quality of resisting change of form; the amount of resistance with which a body opposes change of form; -- opposed to flexibility, ductility, malleability, and softness.

Rima.description: A narrow and elongated aperture; a cleft; a fissure.

Rind.description: The external covering or coat, as of flesh, fruit, trees, etc.; skin; hide; bark; peel; shell.

Rink.description: The smooth and level extent of ice marked off for the game of curling.

Riot.description: Wanton or unrestrained behavior; uproar; tumult.

Ripen.description: To grow ripe; to become mature, as grain, fruit, flowers, and the like; as, grapes ripen in the sun.

Risk.description: Hazard; danger; peril; exposure to loss, injury, or destruction.

Risky.description: Attended with risk or danger; hazardous.

Rist.description: 3d pers. sing. pres. of Rise, contracted from riseth.

Ritual.description: Of or pertaining to rites or ritual; as, ritual service or sacrifices; the ritual law.

Ritualistic.description: Pertaining to, or in accordance with, a ritual; adhering to ritualism.

Rival.description: A person having a common right or privilege with another; a partner.

Rivalry.description: The act of rivaling, or the state of being a rival; a competition.

Rivet.description: A metallic pin with a head, used for uniting two plates or pieces of material together, by passing it through them and then beating or pressing down the point so that it shall spread out and form a second head; a pin or bolt headed or clinched at both ends.

Robin.description: A small European singing bird (Erythacus rubecula), having a reddish breast; -- called also robin redbreast, robinet, and ruddock.

Robinia.description: A genus of leguminous trees including the common locust of North America (Robinia Pseudocacia).

Robust.description: Evincing strength; indicating vigorous health; strong; sinewy; muscular; vigorous; sound; as, a robust body; robust youth; robust health.

Rococo.description: A florid style of ornamentation which prevailed in Europe in the latter part of the eighteenth century.

Rodent.description: Gnawing; biting; corroding; (Med.) applied to a destructive variety of cancer or ulcer.

Roman.description: Of or pertaining to Rome, or the Roman people; like or characteristic of Rome, the Roman people, or things done by Romans; as, Roman fortitude; a Roman aqueduct; Roman art.

Romantic.description: Of or pertaining to romance; involving or resembling romance; hence, fanciful; marvelous; extravagant; unreal; as, a romantic tale; a romantic notion; a romantic undertaking.

Romp.description: To play rudely and boisterously; to leap and frisk about in play.

Rosalia.description: A form of melody in which a phrase or passage is successively repeated, each time a step or half step higher; a melodic sequence.

Rosin.description: The hard, amber-colored resin left after distilling off the volatile oil of turpentine; colophony.

Rostrum.description: The beak or head of a ship.

Rosy.description: Resembling a rose in color, form, or qualities; blooming; red; blushing; also, adorned with roses.

Rota.description: An ecclesiastical court of Rome, called also Rota Romana, that takes cognizance of suits by appeal. It consists of twelve members.

Rotunda.description: A round building; especially, one that is round both on the outside and inside, like the Pantheon at Rome. Less properly, but very commonly, used for a large round room; as, the rotunda of the Capitol at Washington.

Rubicon.description: A small river which separated Italy from Cisalpine Gaul, the province alloted to Julius Caesar.

Ruble.description: The unit of monetary value in Russia.  It is divided into 100 copecks, and in the gold coin of the realm (as in the five and ten ruble pieces) is worth about 77 cents. The silver ruble is a coin worth about 60 cents.

Rubric.description: That part of any work in the early manuscripts and typography which was colored red, to distinguish it from other portions.

Ruby.description: A precious stone of a carmine red color, sometimes verging to violet, or intermediate between carmine and hyacinth red.  It is a red crystallized variety of corundum.

Rudiment.description: That which is unformed or undeveloped; the principle which lies at the bottom of any development; an unfinished beginning.

Ruin.description: The act of falling or tumbling down; fall.

Rumble.description: To make a low, heavy, continued sound; as, the thunder rumbles at a distance.

Rumbling.description: a. & n. from Rumble, v. i.

Rumen.description: The first stomach of ruminants; the paunch; the fardingbag. See Illust. below.

Ruminant.description: Chewing the cud; characterized by chewing again what has been swallowed; of or pertaining to the Ruminantia.

Rump.description: The end of the backbone of an animal, with the parts adjacent; the buttock or buttocks.

Rumple.description: To make uneven; to form into irregular inequalities; to wrinkle; to crumple; as, to rumple an apron or a cravat.

Rundle.description: A round; a step of a ladder; a rung.

Rural.description: Of or pertaining to the country, as distinguished from a city or town; living in the country; suitable for, or resembling, the country; rustic; as, rural scenes; a rural prospect.

Rusk.description: A kind of light, soft bread made with yeast and eggs, often toasted or crisped in an oven; or, a kind of sweetened biscuit.

Rust.description: The reddish yellow coating formed on iron when exposed to moist air, consisting of ferric oxide or hydroxide; hence, by extension, any metallic film of corrosion.

Rustic.description: Of or pertaining to the country; rural; as, the rustic gods of antiquity.

Rusty.description: Covered or affected with rust; as, a rusty knife or sword; rusty wheat.

Sable.description: A carnivorous animal of the Weasel family (Mustela zibellina) native of the northern latitudes of Europe, Asia, and America, -- noted for its fine, soft, and valuable fur.

Sacrament.description: The oath of allegiance taken by Roman soldiers; hence, a sacred ceremony used to impress an obligation; a solemn oath-taking; an oath.

Sacramental.description: Of or pertaining to a sacrament or the sacraments; of the nature of a sacrament; sacredly or solemnly binding; as, sacramental rites or elements.

Sacred.description: Set apart by solemn religious ceremony; especially, in a good sense, made holy; set apart to religious use; consecrated; not profane or common; as, a sacred place; a sacred day; sacred service.

Sacs.description: A tribe of Indians, which, together with the Foxes, formerly occupied the region about Green Bay, Wisconsin.

Saga.description: A Scandinavian legend, or heroic or mythic tradition, among the Norsemen and kindred people; a northern European popular historical or religious tale of olden time.

Sago.description: A dry granulated starch imported from the East Indies, much used for making puddings and as an article of diet for the sick; also, as starch, for stiffening textile fabrics. It is prepared from the stems of several East Indian and Malayan palm trees, but chiefly from the Metroxylon Sagu; also from several cycadaceous plants (Cycas revoluta, Zamia integrifolia, etc.).

Saki.description: Any one of several species of South American monkeys of the genus Pithecia. They have large ears, and a long hairy tail which is not prehensile.

Salable.description: Capable of being sold; fit to be sold; finding a ready market.

Salad.description: A preparation of vegetables, as lettuce, celery, water cress, onions, etc., usually dressed with salt, vinegar, oil, and spice, and eaten for giving a relish to other food; as, lettuce salad; tomato salad, etc.
