Salam.description: A salutation or compliment of ceremony in the east by word or act; an obeisance, performed by bowing very low and placing the right palm on the forehead.

Salient.description: Moving by leaps or springs; leaping; bounding; jumping.

Salina.description: A salt marsh, or salt pond, inclosed from the sea.

Saliva.description: The secretion from the salivary glands.

Salon.description: An apartment for the reception of company; hence, in the plural, fashionable parties; circles of fashionable society.

Salt.description: The chloride of sodium, a substance used for seasoning food, for the preservation of meat, etc. It is found native in the earth, and is also produced, by evaporation and crystallization, from sea water and other water impregnated with saline particles.

Salutatorian.description: The student who pronounces the salutatory oration at the annual Commencement or like exercises of a college, -- an honor commonly assigned to that member of the graduating class who ranks second in scholarship.

Salvia.description: A genus of plants including the sage. See Sage.

Salvo.description: An exception; a reservation; an excuse.

Samaritan.description: Of or pertaining to Samaria, in Palestine.

Sambo.description: A colloquial or humorous appellation for a negro; sometimes, the offspring of a black person and a mulatto; a zambo.

Samoan.description: Of or pertaining to the Samoan Islands (formerly called Navigators' Islands) in the South Pacific Ocean, or their inhabitants.

Samp.description: An article of food consisting of maize broken or bruised, which is cooked by boiling, and usually eaten with milk; coarse hominy.

Sampan.description: A Chinese boat from twelve to fifteen feet long, covered with a house, and sometimes used as a permanent habitation on the inland waters.

Samson.description: An Israelite of Bible record (see Judges xiii.), distinguished for his great strength; hence, a man of extraordinary physical strength.

Sanctify.description: To make sacred or holy; to set apart to a holy or religious use; to consecrate by appropriate rites; to hallow.

Sanctimony.description: Holiness; devoutness; scrupulous austerity; sanctity; especially, outward or artificial saintliness; assumed or pretended holiness; hypocritical devoutness.

Sanctity.description: The state or quality of being sacred or holy; holiness; saintliness; moral purity; godliness.

Sanctuary.description: A sacred place; a consecrated spot; a holy and inviolable site.

Sanctum.description: A sacred place; hence, a place of retreat; a room reserved for personal use; as, an editor's sanctum.

Sand.description: Fine particles of stone, esp. of siliceous stone, but not reduced to dust; comminuted stone in the form of loose grains, which are not coherent when wet.

Sandman.description: A mythical person who makes children sleepy, so that they rub their eyes as if there were sand in them.

Sandy.description: Consisting of, abounding with, or resembling, sand; full of sand; covered or sprinkled with sand; as, a sandy desert, road, or soil.

Sanitary.description: Of or pertaining to health; designed to secure or preserve health; relating to the preservation or restoration of health; hygienic; as, sanitary regulations. See the Note under Sanatory.

Sanity.description: The condition or quality of being sane; soundness of health of body or mind, especially of the mind; saneness.

Sans.description: Without; deprived or destitute of. Rarely used as an English word.

Sanskrit.description: The ancient language of the Hindoos, long since obsolete in vernacular use, but preserved to the present day as the literary and sacred dialect of India. It is nearly allied to the Persian, and to the principal languages of Europe, classical and modern, and by its more perfect preservation of the roots and forms of the primitive language from which they are all descended, is a most important assistance in determining their history and relations. Cf. Prakrit, and Veda.

Santon.description: A Turkish saint; a kind of dervish, regarded by the people as a saint: also, a hermit.

Sarcoma.description: A tumor of fleshy consistence; -- formerly applied to many varieties of tumor, now restricted to a variety of malignant growth made up of cells resembling those of fetal development without any proper intercellular substance.

Sardonic.description: Forced; unnatural; insincere; hence, derisive, mocking, malignant, or bitterly sarcastic; -- applied only to a laugh, smile, or some facial semblance of gayety.

Saros.description: A Chaldean astronomical period or cycle, the length of which has been variously estimated from 3,600 years to 3,600 days, or a little short of 10 years.

Sartorial.description: Of or pertaining to a tailor or his work.

Sartorius.description: A muscle of the thigh, called the tailor's muscle, which arises from the hip bone and is inserted just below the knee. So named because its contraction was supposed to produce the position of the legs assumed by the tailor in sitting.

Satan.description: The grand adversary of man; the Devil, or Prince of darkness; the chief of the fallen angels; the archfiend.

Satin.description: A silk cloth, of a thick, close texture, and overshot woof, which has a glossy surface.

Satirical.description: Of or pertaining to satire; of the nature of satire; as, a satiric style.

Satisfy.description: In general, to fill up the measure of a want of (a person or a thing); hence, to grafity fully the desire of; to make content; to supply to the full, or so far as to give contentment with what is wished for.

Savagery.description: The state of being savage; savageness; savagism.

Savant.description: A man of learning; one versed in literature or science; a person eminent for acquirements.

Scab.description: An incrustation over a sore, wound, vesicle, or pustule, formed by the drying up of the discharge from the diseased part.

Scad.description: A small carangoid fish (Trachurus saurus) abundant on the European coast, and less common on the American. The name is applied also to several allied species.

Scala.description: A machine formerly employed for reducing dislocations of the humerus.

Scald.description: To burn with hot liquid or steam; to pain or injure by contact with, or immersion in, any hot fluid; as, to scald the hand.

Scalp.description: A bed of oysters or mussels.

Scalpel.description: A small knife with a thin, keen blade, -- used by surgeons, and in dissecting.

Scan.description: To mount by steps; to go through with step by step.

Scandal.description: Offense caused or experienced; reproach or reprobation called forth by what is regarded as wrong, criminal, heinous, or flagrant: opprobrium or disgrace.

Scandia.description: A chemical earth, the oxide of scandium.

Scandinavian.description: Of or pertaining to Scandinavia, that is, Sweden, Norway, and Denmark.

Scant.description: Not full, large, or plentiful; scarcely sufficient; less than is wanted for the purpose; scanty; meager; not enough; as, a scant allowance of provisions or water; a scant pattern of cloth for a garment.

Scantily.description: In a scanty manner; not fully; not plentifully; sparingly; parsimoniously.

Scanty.description: Wanting amplitude or extent; narrow; small; not abundant.

Scar.description: A mark in the skin or flesh of an animal, made by a wound or ulcer, and remaining after the wound or ulcer is healed; a cicatrix; a mark left by a previous injury; a blemish; a disfigurement.

Scarcity.description: The quality or condition of being scarce; smallness of quantity in proportion to the wants or demands; deficiency; lack of plenty; short supply; penury; as, a scarcity of grain; a great scarcity of beauties.

Scarlet.description: A deep bright red tinged with orange or yellow, -- of many tints and shades; a vivid or bright red color.

Scarp.description: A band in the same position as the bend sinister, but only half as broad as the latter.

Scary.description: Barren land having only a thin coat of grass.

Scat.description: Go away; begone; away; -- chiefly used in driving off a cat.

Schism.description: Division or separation; specifically (Eccl.), permanent division or separation in the Christian church; breach of unity among people of the same religious faith; the offense of seeking to produce division in a church without justifiable cause.

Scold.description: To find fault or rail with rude clamor; to brawl; to utter harsh, rude, boisterous rebuke; to chide sharply or coarsely; -- often with at; as, to scold at a servant.

Scorn.description: Extreme and lofty contempt; haughty disregard; that disdain which springs from the opinion of the utter meanness and unworthiness of an object.

Scornful.description: Full of scorn or contempt; contemptuous; disdainful.

Scorpion.description: Any one of numerous species of pulmonate arachnids of the order Scorpiones, having a suctorial mouth, large claw-bearing palpi, and a caudal sting.

Scots.description: Of or pertaining to the Scotch; Scotch; Scottish; as, Scots law; a pound Scots (1s. 8d.).

Scovel.description: A mop for sweeping ovens; a malkin.

Scramble.description: To clamber with hands and knees; to scrabble; as, to scramble up a cliff; to scramble over the rocks.

Scrap.description: Something scraped off; hence, a small piece; a bit; a fragment; a detached, incomplete portion.

Scrimp.description: To make too small or short; to limit or straiten; to put on short allowance; to scant; to contract; to shorten; as, to scrimp the pattern of a coat.

Scrip.description: A small bag; a wallet; a satchel.

Scrub.description: To rub hard; to wash with rubbing; usually, to rub with a wet brush, or with something coarse or rough, for the purpose of cleaning or brightening; as, to scrub a floor, a doorplate.

Scruple.description: A weight of twenty grains; the third part of a dram.

Scrupulous.description: Full ofscrupules; inclined to scruple; nicely doubtful; hesitating to determine or to act, from a fear of offending or of doing wrong.

Scrutiny.description: Close examination; minute inspection; critical observation.

Scud.description: To move swiftly; especially, to move as if driven forward by something.

Scum.description: The extraneous matter or impurities which rise to the surface of liquids in boiling or fermentation, or which form on the surface by other means; also, the scoria of metals in a molten state; dross.

Table.description: A smooth, flat surface, like the side of a board; a thin, flat, smooth piece of anything; a slab.

Tablet.description: A small table or flat surface.

Tabling.description: A forming into tables; a setting down in order.

Tabulate.description: To form into a table or tables; to reduce to tables or synopses.

Tabulation.description: The act of forming into a table or tables; as, the tabulation of statistics.

Tacit.description: Done or made in silence; implied, but not expressed; silent; as, tacit consent is consent by silence, or by not interposing an objection.

Tactical.description: Of or pertaining to the art of military and naval tactics.

Tactics.description: The science and art of disposing military and naval forces in order for battle, and performing military and naval evolutions. It is divided into grand tactics, or the tactics of battles, and elementary tactics, or the tactics of instruction.

Talbot.description: A sort of dog, noted for quick scent and eager pursuit of game.

Talc.description: A soft mineral of a soapy feel and a greenish, whitish, or grayish color, usually occurring in foliated masses. It is hydrous silicate of magnesia. Steatite, or soapstone, is a compact granular variety.

Ubiquitous.description: Existing or being everywhere, or in all places, at the same time; omnipresent.

Ugly.description: Offensive to the sight; contrary to beauty; being of disagreeable or loathsome aspect; unsightly; repulsive; deformed.

Ukase.description: In Russia, a published proclamation or imperial order, having the force of law.

Ulmus.description: A genus of trees including the elm.

Ultimatum.description: A final proposition, concession, or condition; especially, the final propositions, conditions, or terms, offered by either of the parties in a diplomatic negotiation; the most favorable terms a negotiator can offer, the rejection of which usually puts an end to the hesitation.

Ultra.description: Going beyond others, or beyond due limit; extreme; fanatical; uncompromising; as, an ultra reformer; ultra measures.

Ultraviolet.description: Lying outside the visible spectrum at its violet end; -- said of rays more refrangible than the extreme violet rays of the spectrum.

Ulva.description: A genus of thin papery bright green seaweeds including the kinds called sea lettuce.

Umbel.description: A kind of flower cluster in which the flower stalks radiate from a common point, as in the carrot and milkweed. It is simple or compound; in the latter case, each peduncle bears another little umbel, called umbellet, or umbellule.

Umbilical.description: Of or pertaining to an umbilicus, or umbilical cord; umbilic.

Umbra.description: The conical shadow projected from a planet or satellite, on the side opposite to the sun, within which a spectator could see no portion of the sun's disk; -- used in contradistinction from penumbra. See Penumbra.

Unable.description: Not able; not having sufficient strength, means, knowledge, skill, or the like; impotent' weak; helpless; incapable; -- now usually followed by an infinitive or an adverbial phrase; as, unable for work; unable to bear fatigue.

Unacceptable.description: Not acceptable; not pleasing; not welcome; unpleasant; disagreeable; displeasing; offensive.

Unanimous.description: Being of one mind; agreeing in opinion, design, or determination; consentient; not discordant or dissentient; harmonious; as, the assembly was unanimous; the members of the council were unanimous.

Unbend.description: To free from flexure; to make, or allow to become, straight; to loosen; as, to unbend a bow.

Unbolt.description: To remove a bolt from; to unfasten; to unbar; to open.

Unborn.description: Not born; no yet brought into life; being still to appear; future.

Unbridled.description: Loosed from the bridle, or as from the bridle; hence, unrestrained; licentious; violent; as, unbridled passions.

Unbroken.description: Not broken; continuous; unsubdued; as, an unbroken colt.

Unbundle.description: To release, as from a bundle; to disclose.

Uncle.description: The brother of one's father or mother; also applied to an aunt's husband; -- the correlative of aunt in sex, and of nephew and niece in relationship.

Uncork.description: To draw the cork from; as, to uncork a bottle.

Uncut.description: Not cut; not separated or divided by cutting or otherwise; -- said especially of books, periodicals, and the like, when the leaves have not been separated by trimming in binding.

Undated.description: Rising and falling in waves toward the margin, as a leaf; waved.

Undeniable.description: Not deniable; incapable of denial; palpably true; indisputable; obvious; as, undeniable evidence.

Undivided.description: Not divided; not separated or disunited; unbroken; whole; continuous; as, plains undivided by rivers or mountains.

Undo.description: To reverse, as what has been done; to annul; to bring to naught.

Unequal.description: Not equal; not matched; not of the same size, length, breadth, quantity, strength, talents, acquirements, age, station, or the like; as, the fingers are of unequal length; peers and commoners are unequal in rank.

Unequivocal.description: Not equivocal; not doubtful; not ambiguous; evident; sincere; plain; as, unequivocal evidence; unequivocal words.

Uneven.description: Not even; not level; not uniform; rough; as, an uneven road or way; uneven ground.

Unfit.description: To make unsuitable or incompetent; to deprive of the strength, skill, or proper qualities for anything; to disable; to incapacitate; to disqualify; as, sickness unfits a man for labor; sin unfits us for the society of holy beings.

Unfold.description: To open the folds of; to expand; to spread out; as, to unfold a tablecloth.

Ungodly.description: Not godly; not having regard for God; disobedient to God; wicked; impious; sinful.

Unholy.description: Not holy; unhallowed; not consecrated; hence, profane; wicked; impious.

Unicellular.description: Having, or consisting of, but a single cell; as, a unicellular organism.

Unification.description: The act of unifying, or the state of being unified.

Unilateral.description: Being on one side only; affecting but one side; one-sided.

Unite.description: To put together so as to make one; to join, as two or more constituents, to form a whole; to combine; to connect; to join; to cause to adhere; as, to unite bricks by mortar; to unite iron bars by welding; to unite two armies.

Universal.description: Of or pertaining to the universe; extending to, including, or affecting, the whole number, quantity, or space; unlimited; general; all-reaching; all-pervading; as, universal ruin; universal good; universal benevolence or benefice.

Universality.description: The quality or state of being universal; unlimited extension or application; generality; -- distinguished from particularity; as, the unversality of a proposition; the unversality of sin; the unversality of the Deluge.

Unjust.description: Acting contrary to the standard of right; not animated or controlled by justice; false; dishonest; as, an unjust man or judge.

Unkempt.description: Not combed; disheveled; as, an urchin with unkempt hair.

Unkind.description: Having no race or kindred; childless.

Unlimited.description: Not limited; having no bounds; boundless; as, an unlimited expanse of ocean.

Unmask.description: To strip of a mask or disguise; to lay open; to expose.

Unmistakable.description: Incapable of being mistaken or misunderstood; clear; plain; obvious; evident.

Unprecedented.description: Having no precedent or example; not preceded by a like case; not having the authority of prior example; novel; new; unexampled.

Unprincipled.description: Being without principles; especially, being without right moral principles; also, characterized by absence of principle.

Unravel.description: To disentangle; to disengage or separate the threads of; as, to unravel a stocking.

Unreality.description: The quality or state of being unreal; want of reality.

Unrest.description: Want of rest or repose; unquietness; sleeplessness; uneasiness; disquietude.

Unruly.description: Not submissive to rule; disregarding restraint; disposed to violate; turbulent; ungovernable; refractory; as, an unruly boy; unruly boy; unruly conduct.

Unset.description: Not set; not fixed or appointed.

Unstable.description: Not stable; not firm, fixed, or constant; subject to change or overthrow.

Untangle.description: To loose from tangles or intricacy; to disentangle; to resolve; as, to untangle thread.

Until.description: To; unto; towards; -- used of material objects.

Unto.description: To; -- now used only in antiquated, formal, or scriptural style. See To.

Untold.description: Not told; not related; not revealed; as, untold secrets.

Unused.description: Not used; as, an unused book; an unused apartment.

Unwary.description: Not vigilant against danger; not wary or cautious; unguarded; precipitate; heedless; careless.

Unwind.description: To wind off; to loose or separate, as what or convolved; to untwist; to untwine; as, to unwind thread; to unwind a ball of yarn.

Uphold.description: To hold up; to lift on high; to elevate.

Upland.description: High land; ground elevated above the meadows and intervals which lie on the banks of rivers, near the sea, or between hills; land which is generally dry; -- opposed to lowland, meadow, marsh, swamp, interval, and the like.

Uplift.description: To lift or raise aloft; to raise; to elevate; as, to uplift the arm; to uplift a rock.

Upon.description: On; -- used in all the senses of that word, with which it is interchangeable.

Upset.description: To set up; to put upright.

Upstart.description: To start or spring up suddenly.

Uranium.description: An element of the chromium group, found in certain rare minerals, as pitchblende, uranite, etc., and reduced as a heavy, hard, nickel-white metal which is quite permanent. Its yellow oxide is used to impart to glass a delicate greenish-yellow tint which is accompanied by a strong fluorescence, and its black oxide is used as a pigment in porcelain painting. Symbol U. Atomic weight 239.

Urea.description: A very soluble crystalline body which is the chief constituent of the urine in mammals and some other animals. It is also present in small quantity in blood, serous fluids, lymph, the liver, etc.

Uric.description: Of or pertaining to urine; obtained from urine; as, uric acid.

Urinary.description: Of or pertaining to the urine; as, the urinary bladder; urinary excretions.

Usage.description: The act of using; mode of using or treating; treatment; conduct with respect to a person or a thing; as, good usage; ill usage; hard usage.

Useful.description: Full of use, advantage, or profit; producing, or having power to produce, good; serviceable for any end or object; helpful toward advancing any purpose; beneficial; profitable; advantageous; as, vessels and instruments useful in a family; books useful for improvement; useful knowledge; useful arts.

Usurp.description: To seize, and hold in possession, by force, or without right; as, to usurp a throne; to usurp the prerogatives of the crown; to usurp power; to usurp the right of a patron is to oust or dispossess him.

Usury.description: A premium or increase paid, or stipulated to be paid, for a loan, as of money; interest.

Uterus.description: The organ of a female mammal in which the young are developed previous to birth; the womb.

Utilization.description: The act of utilizing, or the state of being utilized.

Utilize.description: To make useful; to turn to profitable account or use; to make use of; as, to utilize the whole power of a machine; to utilize one's opportunities.

Utmost.description: Situated at the farthest point or extremity; farthest out; most distant; extreme; as, the utmost limits of the land; the utmost extent of human knowledge.

Vacancy.description: The quality or state of being vacant; emptiness; hence, freedom from employment; intermission; leisure; idleness; listlessness.

Vacant.description: Deprived of contents; not filled; empty; as, a vacant room.

Vacuum.description: A space entirely devoid of matter (called also, by way of distinction, absolute vacuum); hence, in a more general sense, a space, as the interior of a closed vessel, which has been exhausted to a high or the highest degree by an air pump or other artificial means; as, water boils at a reduced temperature in a vacuum.

Vagabond.description: Moving from place to place without a settled habitation; wandering.

Vagina.description: A sheath; a theca; as, the vagina of the portal vein.

Vaginal.description: Of or pertaining to a vagina; resembling a vagina, or sheath; thecal; as, a vaginal synovial membrane; the vaginal process of the temporal bone.

Vagrancy.description: The quality or state of being a vagrant; a wandering without a settled home; an unsettled condition; vagabondism.

Vagrant.description: Moving without certain direction; wandering; erratic; unsettled.

Valedictorian.description: One who pronounces a valedictory address; especially, in American colleges, the student who pronounces the valedictory of the graduating class at the annual commencement, usually the student who ranks first in scholarship.

Valencia.description: A kind of woven fabric for waistcoats, having the weft of wool and the warp of silk or cotton.

Valerian.description: Any plant of the genus Valeriana. The root of the officinal valerian (V. officinalis) has a strong smell, and is much used in medicine as an antispasmodic.

Valiant.description: Vigorous in body; strong; powerful; as, a valiant fencer.

Validity.description: The quality or state of being valid; strength; force; especially, power to convince; justness; soundness; as, the validity of an argument or proof; the validity of an objection.

Validly.description: In a valid manner; so as to be valid.

Valonia.description: The acorn cup of two kinds of oak (Quercus macrolepis, and Q. vallonea) found in Eastern Europe. It contains abundance of tannin, and is much used by tanners and dyers.

Valuable.description: Having value or worth; possessing qualities which are useful and esteemed; precious; costly; as, a valuable horse; valuable land; a valuable cargo.

Valuation.description: The act of valuing, or of estimating value or worth; the act of setting a price; estimation; appraisement; as, a valuation of lands for the purpose of taxation.

Value.description: The property or aggregate properties of a thing by which it is rendered useful or desirable, or the degree of such property or sum of properties; worth; excellence; utility; importance.

Vanadium.description: A rare element of the nitrogen-phosphorus group, found combined, in vanadates, in certain minerals, and reduced as an infusible, grayish-white metallic powder. It is intermediate between the metals and the non-metals, having both basic and acid properties. Symbol V (or Vd, rarely). Atomic weight 51.2.

Vandal.description: One of a Teutonic race, formerly dwelling on the south shore of the Baltic, the most barbarous and fierce of the northern nations that plundered Rome in the 5th century, notorious for destroying the monuments of art and literature.

Vanity.description: The quality or state of being vain; want of substance to satisfy desire; emptiness; unsubstantialness; unrealness; falsity.

Vapid.description: Having lost its life and spirit; dead; spiritless; insipid; flat; dull; unanimated; as, vapid beer; a vapid speech; a vapid state of the blood.

Vara.description: A Spanish measure of length equal to about one yard. The vara now in use equals 33.385 inches.

Vari.description: The ringtailed lemur (Lemur catta) of Madagascar. Its long tail is annulated with black and white.

Variability.description: The quality or state of being variable; variableness.

Variable.description: Having the capacity of varying or changing; capable of alternation in any manner; changeable; as, variable winds or seasons; a variable quantity.

Variant.description: Varying in from, character, or the like; variable; different; diverse.

Varvel.description: In falconry, one of the rings secured to the ends of the jesses.

Vary.description: To change the aspect of; to alter in form, appearance, substance, position, or the like; to make different by a partial change; to modify; as, to vary the properties, proportions, or nature of a thing; to vary a posture or an attitude; to vary one's dress or opinions.

Vascular.description: Consisting of, or containing, vessels as an essential part of a structure; full of vessels; specifically (Bot.), pertaining to, or containing, special ducts, or tubes, for the circulation of sap.

Vastly.description: To a vast extent or degree; very greatly; immensely.

Vatican.description: A magnificent assemblage of buildings at Rome, near the church of St. Peter, including the pope's palace, a museum, a library, a famous chapel, etc.

Veda.description: The ancient sacred literature of the Hindus; also, one of the four collections, called Rig-Veda, Yajur-Veda, Sama-Veda, and Atharva-Veda, constituting the most ancient portions of that literature.

Vega.description: A brilliant star of the first magnitude, the brightest of those constituting the constellation Lyra.

Vegetal.description: Of or pertaining to vegetables, or the vegetable kingdom; of the nature of a vegetable; vegetable.

Vegetarian.description: One who holds that vegetables and fruits are the only proper food for man.  Strict vegetarians eat no meat, eggs, or milk.

Vehicle.description: That in or on which any person or thing is, or may be, carried, as a coach, carriage, wagon, cart, car, sleigh, bicycle, etc.; a means of conveyance; specifically, a means of conveyance upon land.

Vehicular.description: Of or pertaining to a vehicle; serving as a vehicle; as, a vehicular contrivance.

Velocity.description: Quickness of motion; swiftness; speed; celerity; rapidity; as, the velocity of wind; the velocity of a planet or comet in its orbit or course; the velocity of a cannon ball; the velocity of light.

Velvet.description: A silk fabric, having a short, close nap of erect threads. Inferior qualities are made with a silk pile on a cotton or linen back.

Velvety.description: Made of velvet, or like velvet; soft; smooth; delicate.

Venal.description: Of or pertaining to veins; venous; as, venal blood.

Venality.description: The quality or state of being venal, or purchasable; mercenariness; prostitution of talents, offices, or services, for money or reward; as, the venality of a corrupt court; the venality of an official.

Venereal.description: Of or pertaining to venery, or sexual love; relating to sexual intercourse.

Venom.description: Matter fatal or injurious to life; poison; particularly, the poisonous, the poisonous matter which certain animals, such as serpents, scorpions, bees, etc., secrete in a state of health, and communicate by thing or stinging.

Ventral.description: Of, pertaining to, or situated near, the belly, or ventral side, of an animal or of one of its parts; hemal; abdominal; as, the ventral fin of a fish; the ventral root of a spinal nerve; -- opposed to dorsal.

Ventricular.description: Of or pertaining to a ventricle; bellied.

Venue.description: A neighborhood or near place; the place or county in which anything is alleged to have happened; also, the place where an action is laid.

Venus.description: The goddess of beauty and love, that is, beauty or love deified.

Verify.description: To make into a verb; to use as a verb; to verbalize.

Veritable.description: Agreeable to truth or to fact; actual; real; true; genuine.

Verity.description: The quality or state of being true, or real; consonance of a statement, proposition, or other thing, with fact; truth; reality.

Vertex.description: A turning point; the principal or highest point; top; summit; crown; apex.

Vesicle.description: A bladderlike vessel; a membranous cavity; a cyst; a cell.

Vespa.description: A genus of Hymenoptera including the common wasps and hornets.

Vest.description: An article of clothing covering the person; an outer garment; a vestment; a dress; a vesture; a robe.

Vesta.description: One of the great divinities of the ancient Romans, identical with the Greek Hestia. She was a virgin, and the goddess of the hearth; hence, also, of the fire on it, and the family round it.

Vestal.description: Of or pertaining to Vesta, the virgin goddess of the hearth; hence, pure; chaste.

Vestibule.description: The porch or entrance into a house; a hall or antechamber next the entrance; a lobby; a porch; a hall.

Vestigial.description: Of or pertaining to a vestige or remnant; like a vestige.

Veto.description: An authoritative prohibition or negative; a forbidding; an interdiction.

Viability.description: The quality or state of being viable.

Viable.description: Capable of living; born alive and with such form and development of organs as to be capable of living; -- said of a newborn, or a prematurely born, infant.

Viaduct.description: A structure of considerable magnitude, usually with arches or supported on trestles, for carrying a road, as a railroad, high above the ground or water; a bridge; especially, one for crossing a valley or a gorge.  Cf. Trestlework.

Vial.description: A small bottle, usually of glass; a little glass vessel with a narrow aperture intended to be closed with a stopper; as, a vial of medicine.

Vibrancy.description: The state of being vibrant; resonance.

Vibrant.description: Vibrating; tremulous; resonant; as, vibrant drums.

Vicinity.description: The quality or state of being near, or not remote; nearness; propinquity; proximity; as, the value of the estate was increased by the vicinity of two country seats.

Victim.description: A living being sacrificed to some deity, or in the performance of a religious rite; a creature immolated, or made an offering of.

Victoria.description: A genus of aquatic plants named in honor of Queen Victoria.  The Victoria regia is a native of Guiana and Brazil. Its large, spreading leaves are often over five feet in diameter, and have a rim from three to five inches high; its immense rose-white flowers sometimes attain a diameter of nearly two feet.

Victorian.description: Of or pertaining to the reign of Queen Victoria of England; as, the Victorian poets.

Waft.description: To give notice to by waving something; to wave the hand to; to beckon.

Wages.description: A compensation given to a hired person for services; price paid for labor; recompense; hire.  See Wage, n., 2.

Wagon.description: A wheeled carriage; a vehicle on four wheels, and usually drawn by horses; especially, one used for carrying freight or merchandise.

Waken.description: To wake; to cease to sleep; to be awakened.

Wald.description: A forest; -- used as a termination of names.  See Weald.

Walnut.description: The fruit or nut of any tree of the genus Juglans; also, the tree, and its timber. The seven or eight known species are all natives of the north temperate zone.

Walrus.description: A very large marine mammal (Trichecus rosmarus) of the Seal family, native of the Arctic Ocean. The male has long and powerful tusks descending from the upper jaw. It uses these in procuring food and in fighting.  It is hunted for its oil, ivory, and skin. It feeds largely on mollusks. Called also morse.

Waltz.description: A dance performed by two persons in circular figures with a whirling motion; also, a piece of music composed in triple measure for this kind of dance.

Wamble.description: To heave; to be disturbed by nausea; -- said of the stomach.

Wampum.description: Beads made of shells, used by the North American Indians as money, and also wrought into belts, etc., as an ornament.

Wand.description: A small stick; a rod; a verge.

Want.description: The state of not having; the condition of being without anything; absence or scarcity of what is needed or desired; deficiency; lack; as, a want of power or knowledge for any purpose; want of food and clothing.

Wanton.description: Untrained; undisciplined; unrestrained; hence, loose; free; luxuriant; roving; sportive.

Wantonly.description: In a wanton manner; without regularity or restraint; loosely; sportively; gayly; playfully; recklessly; lasciviously.

Wapiti.description: The American elk (Cervus Canadensis). It is closely related to the European red deer, which it somewhat exceeds in size.

Warble.description: A small, hard tumor which is produced on the back of a horse by the heat or pressure of the saddle in traveling.

Ward.description: The act of guarding; watch; guard; guardianship; specifically, a guarding during the day.  See the Note under Watch, n., 1.

Warden.description: A keeper; a guardian; a watchman.

Warm.description: Having heat in a moderate degree; not cold as, warm milk.

Warp.description: To throw; hence, to send forth, or throw out, as words; to utter.

Wart.description: A small, usually hard, tumor on the skin formed by enlargement of its vascular papillae, and thickening of the epidermis which covers them.

Wary.description: Cautious of danger; carefully watching and guarding against deception, artifices, and dangers; timorously or suspiciously prudent; circumspect; scrupulous; careful.

Wasp.description: Any one of numerous species of stinging hymenopterous insects, esp. any of the numerous species of the genus Vespa, which includes the true, or social, wasps, some of which are called yellow jackets.

Xebec.description: A small three-masted vessel, with projecting bow stern and convex decks, used in the Mediterranean for transporting merchandise, etc. It carries large square sails, or both. Xebecs were formerly armed and used by corsairs.

Yard.description: A rod; a stick; a staff.

Yarn.description: Spun wool; woolen thread; also, thread of other material, as of cotton, flax, hemp, or silk; material spun and prepared for use in weaving, knitting, manufacturing sewing thread, or the like.

Yoga.description: A species of asceticism among the Hindoos, which consists in a complete abstraction from all worldly objects, by which the votary expects to obtain union with the universal spirit, and to acquire superhuman faculties.

Yogi.description: A follower of the yoga philosophy; an ascetic.

Yuen.description: The crowned gibbon (Hylobates pileatus), native of Siam, Southern China, and the Island of Hainan. It is entirely arboreal in its habits, and has very long arms. the males are dark brown or blackish, with a caplike mass of long dark hair, and usually with a white band around the face. The females are yellowish white, with a dark spot on the breast and another on the crown. Called also wooyen, and wooyen ape.

Zambo.description: The child of a mulatto and a negro; also, the child of an Indian and a negro; colloquially or humorously, a negro; a sambo.

Zebra.description: Either one of two species of South African wild horses remarkable for having the body white or yellowish white, and conspicuously marked with dark brown or brackish bands.

Zest.description: A piece of orange or lemon peel, or the aromatic oil which may be squeezed from such peel, used to give flavor to liquor, etc.

Zeta.description: A Greek letter  corresponding to our z.

Zigzag.description: Something that has short turns or angles.

Zinc.description: An abundant element of the magnesium-cadmium group, extracted principally from the minerals zinc blende, smithsonite, calamine, and franklinite, as an easily fusible bluish white metal, which is malleable, especially when heated. It is not easily oxidized in moist air, and hence is used for sheeting, coating galvanized iron, etc. It is used in making brass, britannia, and other alloys, and is also largely consumed in electric batteries. Symbol Zn. Atomic weight 64.9.

Zion.description: A hill in Jerusalem, which, after the capture of that city by the Israelites, became the royal residence of David and his successors.

form.description: A suffix used to denote in the form / shape of, resembling, etc.; as, valiform; oviform.
